'''Google LLC'''<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-01/alphabet-wraps-up-reorganization-with-a-new-company-called-xxvi |title=Alphabet Finishes Reorganization With New XXVI Company |date=September 1, 2017 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=October 31, 2017}}</ref> is an American multinational technology company that specializes in Internet-related services and products, which include [[online advertising|online advertising technologies]], [[search engine]], [[cloud computing]], software, and hardware. Google was founded in 1998 by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] while they were Ph.D. students at [[Stanford University]] in [[California]]. Together they own about 14 percent of its shares and control 56 percent of the stockholder voting power through [[Preferred stock|supervoting]] stock. They incorporated Google as a privately held company on September 4, 1998. An initial public offering (IPO) took place on August 19, 2004, and Google moved to its headquarters in Mountain View, California, nicknamed the [[Googleplex]]. In August 2015, Google announced plans to reorganize its various interests as a conglomerate called [[Alphabet Inc.]] Google is Alphabet's leading subsidiary and will continue to be the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet interests. [[Sundar Pichai]] was appointed CEO of Google, replacing Larry Page who became the CEO of Alphabet.

The company's rapid growth since incorporation has triggered a chain of products, acquisitions, and partnerships beyond Google's core search engine ([[Google Search]]). It offers services designed for work and productivity ([[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets]], and [[Google Slides]]), email ([[Gmail]]/[[Inbox by Gmail|Inbox]]), scheduling and time management ([[Google Calendar]]), cloud storage ([[Google Drive]]), social networking ([[Google+]]), instant messaging and video chat ([[Google Allo]], [[Google Duo|Duo]], [[Hangouts]]), language translation ([[Google Translate]]), mapping and navigation ([[Google Maps]], [[Waze]], [[Google Earth]], [[Street View]]), video sharing ([[YouTube]]), note-taking ([[Google Keep]]), and photo organizing and editing ([[Google Photos]]). The company leads the development of the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] mobile operating system, the [[Google Chrome]] web browser, and [[Chrome OS]], a lightweight operating system based on the Chrome browser. Google has moved increasingly into hardware; from 2010 to 2015, it partnered with major electronics manufacturers in the production of its [[Google Nexus|Nexus]] devices, and it released multiple hardware products in October 2016, including the [[Pixel (smartphone)|Google Pixel]] smartphone, [[Google Home]] smart speaker, [[Google Wifi]] mesh wireless router, and [[Google Daydream]] virtual reality headset. Google has also experimented with becoming an Internet carrier. In February 2010, it announced [[Google Fiber]], a fiber-optic infrastructure that was installed in Kansas City; in April 2015, it launched [[Project Fi]] in the United States, combining Wi-Fi and cellular networks from different providers; and in 2016, it announced the Google Station initiative to make public Wi-Fi available around the world, with initial deployment in India.<ref>Sam Byford, The Verge. "[https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india Google Station is a new platform that aims to make public Wi-Fi better]." September 27, 2016. Retrieved May 22, 2018.</ref>

[[Alexa Internet]] monitors commercial web traffic and lists Google.com as the most visited website in the world. Several other Google services also figure in the top 100 most visited websites, including [[YouTube]] and [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]]. Google is the most valuable brand in the world {{as of|2017|lc=y|post=,}}<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/worlds-most-valuable-brands-facebook-google-apple-amazon-a7556571.html |title=Google is now the world's most valuable brand |date=February 1, 2017 |work=The Independent|access-date=August 31, 2017 |language=en-GB}}</ref> but has received significant [[Criticism of Google|criticism]] involving issues such as [[Privacy concerns regarding Google|privacy concerns]], tax avoidance, antitrust, [[Censorship by Google|censorship]], and search neutrality. Google's [[mission statement]] is "to organize the world's information and make it universally accessible and useful", and its unofficial slogan was "Don't be evil". In October 2015, the motto was replaced in the Alphabet corporate code of conduct by the phrase ''"Do the right thing"'', while the original one was retained in the code of conduct of Google.<ref name=":0" /> Around May 2018, the slogan was silently removed from the code's clauses, leaving only one generic reference in its last paragraph.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gizmodo.com/google-removes-nearly-all-mentions-of-dont-be-evil-from-1826153393|title=Google Removes 'Don't Be Evil' Clause From Its Code of Conduct|first=Kate|last=Conger|publisher=}}</ref>

== History ==
{{Main|History of Google}}
[[File:Google1998.png|thumb|upright=1.15|Google's original homepage had a simple design because the company founders had little experience in [[HTML]], the [[markup language]] used for designing web pages.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://alan.blog-city.com/an_evening_with_googles_marissa_mayer.htm |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/61rJXKAeq?url=http://alan.blog-city.com/an_evening_with_googles_marissa_mayer.htm |archivedate=September 21, 2011 |title=An evening with Google's Marissa Mayer |last=Williamson |first=Alan |website=Alan Williamson |date=January 12, 2005 |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |deadurl=yes }}</ref>|alt=Google's homepage in 1998]] Google began in January 1996 as a research project by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] when they were both PhD students at [[Stanford University]] in [[Stanford, California]].<ref name="milestones">{{cite web |title=Our history in depth |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/history/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401005940/http://www.google.com/about/company/history/ |website=Google Company |archivedate=April 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 15, 2017 |deadurl=yes }}</ref>

While conventional search engines ranked results by counting how many times the search terms appeared on the page, the two theorized about a better system that analyzed the relationships among websites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ilpubs.stanford.edu:8090/422/ |title=The PageRank Citation Ranking: Bringing Order to the Web |last1=Page |first1=Lawrence |last2=Brin |first2=Sergey |last3=Motwani |first3=Rajeev |last4=Winograd |first4=Terry |date=November 11, 1999 |website=Stanford University |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091118014915/http://ilpubs.stanford.edu:8090/422/ |archive-date=November 18, 2009 |dead-url=yes |df=mdy-all }}</ref> They called this new technology [[PageRank]]; it determined a website's [[Relevance (information retrieval)|relevance]] by the number of pages, and the importance of those pages that linked back to the original site.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/corporate/tech.html |title=Technology Overview |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www-diglib.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/WP/get/SIDL-WP-1997-0072?1 |title=PageRank: Bringing Order to the Web |last=Page |first=Larry |website=Stanford Digital Library Project |date=August 18, 1997 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20020506051802/http://www-diglib.stanford.edu/cgi-bin/WP/get/SIDL-WP-1997-0072?1 |archivedate=May 6, 2002 |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes }}</ref>

Page and Brin originally nicknamed their new search engine "BackRub", because the system checked backlinks to estimate the importance of a site.<ref>{{Cite news |title=The Birth of Google |first=John |last=Battelle |newspaper=Wired |date=August 2005 |url=https://www.wired.com/wired/archive/13.08/battelle.html?tw=wn_tophead_4 |accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Trex |first1=Ethan |title=9 People, Places & Things That Changed Their Names |url=http://mentalfloss.com/article/20890/9-people-places-things-changed-their-names |website=Mental Floss |accessdate=August 4, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://huron.stanford.edu |title=Backrub search engine at Stanford University |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19961224105215/http://huron.stanford.edu/ |archivedate=December 24, 1996 |accessdate=March 12, 2011}}</ref> Eventually, they changed the name to Google; the name of the search engine originated from a misspelling of the word "[[googol]]",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html |title=Origin of the name "Google" |last=Koller |first=David |date=January 2004 |website=Stanford University |accessdate=July 4, 2012 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/68ubHzYs7?url=http://graphics.stanford.edu/~dk/google_name_origin.html |archivedate=July 4, 2012 |deadurl=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327141327/http://www.stanforddaily.com/2003/02/12/from-googol-to-google |archivedate=March 27, 2010 |title=From Googol to Google |last=Hanley |first=Rachael |date=February 12, 2003 |newspaper=The Stanford Daily |publisher=Stanford University |accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> the number 1 followed by 100 zeros, which was picked to signify that the search engine was intended to provide large quantities of information.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/company.html |title=Google! Beta website |website=Google, Inc. |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990221202430/https://www.google.com/company.html |archivedate=February 21, 1999 |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> Originally, Google ran under Stanford University's website, with the domains ''google.stanford.edu''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://google.stanford.edu |title=Google! Search Engine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981111183552/http://google.stanford.edu/ |website=Stanford University |archivedate=November 11, 1998 |accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref> and ''z.stanford.edu''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://z.stanford.edu/ |title=Google! Search Engine |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19981201235013/http://z.stanford.edu/ |website=Stanford University |archivedate=December 1, 1998 |accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref>

The domain name for Google was registered on September 15, 1997,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://whois.domaintools.com/google.com |title=Google.com WHOIS, DNS, & Domain Info - DomainTools |website=[[WHOIS]] |date= |accessdate=July 11, 2016}}</ref> and the company was incorporated on September 4, 1998. It was based in the garage of a friend ([[Susan Wojcicki]]<ref name="milestones"/>) in [[Menlo Park, California]]. [[Craig Silverstein]], a fellow PhD student at Stanford, was hired as the first employee.<ref name="milestones"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www-cs-students.stanford.edu/~csilvers/ |title=Craig Silverstein's website |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19991002122809/http://www-cs-students.stanford.edu/~csilvers/ |archivedate=October 2, 1999 |website=Stanford University |accessdate=October 12, 2010 |deadurl=yes }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Kopytoff |first=Verne |url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2008-09-07/news/17161124_1_larry-page-google-search-engine |title=Craig Silverstein grew a decade with Google |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=Hearst Communications, Inc. |date=September 7, 2008 |accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref>

=== Financing (1998) and initial public offering (2004) ===
[[File:Google’s First Production Server.jpg|upright|thumb|Google's first production server.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.computerhistory.org/collections/accession/102662167 |title=Google Server Assembly |website=Computer History Museum |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref>|alt=Google's first servers, showing lots of exposed wiring and circuit boards]]

Google was initially funded by an August 1998 contribution of $100,000 from [[Andy Bechtolsheim]], co-founder of [[Sun Microsystems]]; the money was given before Google was incorporated.<ref name="Bechtolsheim">{{Cite news |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/chronicle/archive/2004/04/29/MNGLD6CFND34.DTL |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090919030812/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=%2Fchronicle%2Farchive%2F2004%2F04%2F29%2FMNGLD6CFND34.DTL |archivedate=September 19, 2009 |title=For early Googlers, key word is $$ |last=Kopytoff |first=Verne |date=April 29, 2004 |newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=Hearst Communications |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=San Francisco |deadurl=yes }}</ref> Google received money from three other [[angel investor]]s in 1998: [[Amazon.com]] founder [[Jeff Bezos]], Stanford University computer science professor [[David Cheriton]], and entrepreneur [[Ram Shriram]].<ref name="1998 Investments">''On September 7, 1998, the day Google officially incorporated, he [Shriram] wrote out a check for just over $250,000, one of four of this size the founders received.'' {{Cite book |title=Googled: The End of the World As We Know It |last=Auletta |first=Ken |date=October 26, 2010 |publisher=Penguin Books |isbn=9780143118046 |edition=Reprint |location=New York, N.Y. |language=English}}</ref>

After some additional, small investments through the end of 1998 to early 1999,<ref name="1998 Investments"/> a new $25 million round of funding was announced on June 7, 1999,<ref>{{Cite press release |url=https://www.google.com/pressrel/pressrelease1.html |archiveurl=https://www.google.com/press/pressrel/pressrelease1.html |archivedate=March 9, 2000 |title=Google Receives $25&nbsp;Million in Equity Funding |date=June 7, 1999 |location=Palo Alto, Calif. |publisher=Google |accessdate=February 16, 2009}}</ref> with major investors including the [[venture capital]] firms [[Kleiner Perkins Caufield & Byers]] and [[Sequoia Capital]].<ref name="Bechtolsheim" />

Early in 1999, Brin and Page decided they wanted to sell Google to [[Excite]]. They went to Excite CEO George Bell and offered to sell it to him for $1 million. He rejected the offer. [[Vinod Khosla]], one of Excite's venture capitalists, talked the duo down to $750,000, but Bell still rejected it.<ref>{{cite web |first=MG |last=Siegler |title=When Google Wanted To Sell To Excite For Under $1 Million — And They Passed |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/09/29/google-excite/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=September 29, 2010 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>

Google's [[initial public offering]] (IPO) took place five years later, on August 19, 2004. At that time Larry Page, Sergey Brin, and [[Eric Schmidt]] agreed to work together at Google for 20 years, until the year 2024.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2008/01/18/news/companies/google.fortune/index.htm |title=Google wins again |date=January 29, 2008 |newspaper=Fortune |publisher=Time Warner |accessdate=January 22, 2011 |first=Adam |last=Lashinsky}}</ref>

At IPO, the company offered 19,605,052 shares at a price of $85 per share.<ref name="IPO">{{Cite news |url=http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/aug2004/tc20040819_6843_tc120.htm |title=Google: Whiz Kids or Naughty Boys? |last=Elgin |first=Ben |date=August 19, 2004 |newspaper=BusinessWeek |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT7Hw63l?url=http://www.businessweek.com/technology/content/aug2004/tc20040819_6843_tc120.htm |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |deadurl=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://investor.google.com/pdf/2004_AnnualReport.pdf |title=2004 Annual Report |year=2004 |website=Google, Inc. |page=29 |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=Mountain View, California}}</ref> Shares were sold in an online auction format using a system built by [[Morgan Stanley]] and [[Credit Suisse]], underwriters for the deal.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://money.cnn.com/2004/04/29/technology/google/ |title=Google sets $2.7&nbsp;billion IPO |last=La Monica |first=Paul R. |date=April 30, 2004 |work=CNN Money |accessdate=February 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/want-in-on-googles-ipo/135799 |title=Want In on Google's IPO? |last=Kawamoto |first=Dawn |date=April 29, 2004 |website=ZDNet |accessdate=February 19, 2010}}</ref> The sale of $1.67 bn (billion) gave Google a [[market capitalization]] of more than $23bn.<ref name="washpost">{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A14939-2004Aug19.html |title=Google's IPO: Grate Expectations |last=Webb |first=Cynthia L. |newspaper=The Washington Post |accessdate=February 19, 2010 |location=Washington, D.C. |date=August 19, 2004}}</ref> By January 2014, its market capitalization had grown to $397bn.<ref name="Marketwatch">{{cite web |title=Google Overview |url=http://www.marketwatch.com/investing/stock/goog |website=Marketwatch |accessdate=February 2, 2014}}</ref> The vast majority of the 271&nbsp;million shares remained under the control of Google, and many Google employees became instant paper millionaires. [[Yahoo!]], a competitor of Google, also benefitted because it owned 8.4&nbsp;million shares of Google before the IPO took place.<ref name="yahooshares">{{Cite web |url=http://www.internetnews.com/bus-news/article.php/3392781 |title=Yahoo and Google Settle |last=Kuchinskas |first=Susan |date=August 9, 2004 |website=internetnews.com |accessdate=February 19, 2010}}</ref>

There were concerns that Google's IPO would lead to changes in company culture. Reasons ranged from shareholder pressure for employee benefit reductions to the fact that many company executives would become instant paper millionaires.<ref>{{Cite news |agency=Associated Press |url=https://www.wired.com/techbiz/media/news/2004/04/63241 |title=Quirky Google Culture Endangered? |newspaper=Wired |date=April 28, 2004 |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100814174333/http://www.wired.com/techbiz/media/news/2004/04/63241 |archivedate=August 14, 2010}}</ref> As a reply to this concern, co-founders Brin and Page promised in a report to potential investors that the IPO would not change the company's culture.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Olsen |first1=Stefanie |last2=Kawamoto |first2=Dawn |url=http://news.cnet.com/2100-1024-5201978.html |title=Google IPO at $2.7&nbsp;billion |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=April 30, 2004 |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> In 2005, articles in ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{cite web |first=Gary |last=Rivlin |title=Relax, Bill Gates; It's Google's Turn as the Villain |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/08/24/technology/relax-bill-gates-its-googles-turn-as-the-villain.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 24, 2005 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> and other sources began suggesting that Google had lost its anti-corporate, no evil philosophy.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Utz, Richard |title=The Good Corporation? Google's Medievalism and Why It Matters |journal=Studies in Medievalism |volume=23 |date=2013 |pages=21–28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last1=Gibson |first1=Owen |last2=Wray |first2=Richard |url=http://www.smh.com.au/news/technology/search-giant-may-outgrow-its-fans/2005/08/25/1124562975596.html3001.asp |title=Search giant may outgrow its fans |newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=August 25, 2005 |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Ranka |first=Mohit |url=http://www.osnews.com/story/17928/Google--Dont-Be-Evil |title=Google&nbsp;– Don't Be Evil |publisher=OSNews |date=May 17, 2007 |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref>
In an effort to maintain the company's unique culture, Google designated a Chief Culture Officer, who also serves as the Director of Human Resources. The purpose of the Chief Culture Officer is to develop and maintain the culture and work on ways to keep true to the core values that the company was founded on: a flat organization with a collaborative environment.<ref name="CCO">{{cite web |last=Mills |first=Elinor |url=http://www.zdnet.com.au/meet-google-s-culture-czar-339275147.htm |title=Google's culture czar |website=ZDNet |date=April 30, 2007 |accessdate=November 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101031155723/http://www.zdnet.com.au/meet-google-s-culture-czar-339275147.htm |archivedate=October 31, 2010}}</ref> Google has also faced allegations of [[sexism]] and [[ageism]] from former employees.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kawamoto |first=Dawn |url=http://news.cnet.com/Google-hit-with-job-discrimination-lawsuit/2100-1030_3-5807158.html?tag=nl |title=Google hit with job discrimination lawsuit |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=July 27, 2005 |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google accused of ageism in reinstated lawsuit |url=http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071006/google_old_071006/20071006 |website=ctv.ca |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011205140/http://www.ctv.ca/servlet/ArticleNews/story/CTVNews/20071006/google_old_071006/20071006 |date=October 6, 2007 |archivedate=October 11, 2007 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> In 2013, a [[High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation|class action against]] several [[Silicon Valley]] companies, including Google, was filed for alleged "no cold call" agreements which restrained the recruitment of high-tech employees.<ref>{{cite web |first=Seth |last=Rosenblatt |title=Judge approves first payout in antitrust wage-fixing lawsuit |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/judge-approves-first-payout-in-antitrust-wage-fixing-lawsuit/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=May 16, 2014 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>

The stock performed well after the IPO, with shares hitting $350 for the first time on October 31, 2007,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://weblogs.baltimoresun.com/business/hancock/blog/2007/10/google_shares_hit_700.html |title=Google shares hit $700 |date=October 31, 2007 |last=Hancock |first=Jay |work=The Baltimore Sun |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> primarily because of strong sales and earnings in the [[online advertising]] market.<ref name="bowlingforgoogle">{{Cite news |last=La Monica |first=Paul R. |url=http://money.cnn.com/2005/05/25/technology/techinvestor/lamonica/index.htm |title=Bowling for Google |work=CNN |date=May 25, 2005 |accessdate=February 28, 2007}}</ref> The surge in stock price was fueled mainly by individual investors, as opposed to large institutional investors and [[mutual fund]]s.<ref name="bowlingforgoogle" /> GOOG shares split into GOOG [[class C share]]s and GOOGL [[class A share]]s.<ref>{{cite web |title=This could cost Google more than $500 million |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/04/02/stock-split-could-cost-google-over-500-million.html |website=CNBC |accessdate=December 30, 2015}}</ref> The company is listed on the [[NASDAQ]] stock exchange under the [[ticker symbol]]s GOOGL and GOOG, and on the [[Frankfurt Stock Exchange]] under the ticker symbol GGQ1. These ticker symbols now refer to Alphabet Inc., Google's holding company, {{as of|2015|8|10|alt=since the fourth quarter of 2015.}}<ref>{{Cite news |first=Jacob |last=Pramuk |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2015/08/10/google-announces-plans-for-new-operating-structure.html |title=Google to become part of new company, Alphabet |date=August 10, 2015 |accessdate=August 11, 2015 |newspaper=[[CNBC]]}}</ref>

=== Growth ===
In March 1999, the company moved its offices to [[Palo Alto, California]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Weinberger |title=38 photos of Google's rise from a Stanford dorm room to world domination |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/google-history-in-photos-2015-10 |website=[[Business Insider]] |publisher=[[Axel Springer SE]] |date=October 12, 2015 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref> which is home to several prominent [[Silicon Valley]] technology start-ups.<ref>{{cite web |title=A building blessed with tech success |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/a-building-blessed-with-tech-success/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref> The next year, Google began selling advertisements associated with search keywords against Page and Brin's initial opposition toward an advertising-funded search engine.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Stross |first=Randall |title=Planet Google: One Company's Audacious Plan to Organize Everything We Know |publisher=Free Press |location=New York |date=September 2008 |pages=3–4 |chapter=Introduction |isbn=978-1-4165-4691-7 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=xOk3EIUW9VgC&printsec=frontcover |accessdate=February 14, 2010 |chapterurl=https://books.google.com/?id=xOk3EIUW9VgC&printsec=frontcover}}</ref><ref name="milestones" /> To maintain an uncluttered page design, advertisements were solely text-based.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Launches Self-Service Advertising Program |url=http://www.google.com/press/pressrel/pressrelease39.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401005413/http://www.google.com/press/pressrel/pressrelease39.html |website=News from Google |date=October 23, 2000 |archivedate=April 1, 2012 |accessdate=July 15, 2017}}</ref>

This model of selling keyword advertising was first pioneered by Goto.com, an [[Idealab]] spin-off created by [[Bill T. Gross|Bill Gross]].<ref name="goto strong">{{Cite web |url=http://searchenginewatch.com/2166331 |title=GoTo Going Strong |last=Sullivan |first=Danny |date=July 1, 1998 |website=SearchEngineWatch |accessdate=February 18, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091014204451/http://searchenginewatch.com/2166331 |archivedate=October 14, 2009}}</ref><ref name="cnet p4p">{{Cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/Pay-for-placement-gets-another-shot/2100-1023_3-208309.html |title=Pay-for-placement gets another shot |last=Pelline |first=Jeff |date=February 19, 1998 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 18, 2010}}</ref> When the company changed names to Overture Services, it sued Google over alleged infringements of the company's pay-per-click and bidding patents. Overture Services would later be bought by Yahoo! and renamed [[Yahoo! Search Marketing]]. The case was then settled out of court; Google agreed to issue shares of common stock to Yahoo! in exchange for a perpetual license.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/Google,-Yahoo-bury-the-legal-hatchet/2100-1024_3-5302421.html |title=Google, Yahoo bury the legal hatchet |last=Olsen |first=Stephanie |date=August 9, 2004 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 18, 2010}}</ref>

In 2001, Google received a patent for its PageRank mechanism.<ref name="patent">{{Ref patent |country=US |number=6285999 |status=patent |title=Method for node ranking in a linked database |gdate=September 4, 2001 |fdate=January 9, 1998 |invent1=Page, Lawrence |assign1=The Board of Trustees of the Leland Stanford Junior University |class=G06F17/30}}</ref> The patent was officially assigned to Stanford University and lists Lawrence Page as the inventor. In 2003, after outgrowing two other locations, the company leased an office complex from [[Silicon Graphics]], at 1600 Amphitheatre Parkway in [[Mountain View, California]].<ref name="sgibldg">{{Cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/Googles-movin-on-up/2110-1032_3-1025111.html |title=Google's movin' on up |last=Olsen |first=Stephanie |date=July 11, 2003 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 15, 2010}}</ref> The complex became known as the [[Googleplex]], a play on the word [[googolplex]], the number one followed by a googol zeroes. The [[Googleplex]] interiors were designed by [[Clive Wilkinson]] Architects. Three years later, Google bought the property from SGI for $319&nbsp;million.<ref name="googleplexpurchase">{{Cite news |url=http://sanjose.bizjournals.com/sanjose/stories/2006/06/19/newscolumn3.html |title=Google to buy headquarters building from Silicon Graphics |date=June 16, 2006 |newspaper=Silicon Valley / San Jose Business Journal |publisher=American City Business Journals |accessdate=February 15, 2010 |location=San Jose}}</ref> By that time, the name "Google" had found its way into everyday language, causing the verb "[[google (verb)|google]]" to be added to the ''[[Merriam-Webster]] Collegiate Dictionary'' and the ''[[Oxford English Dictionary]]'', denoted as: "to use the Google search engine to obtain information on the Internet".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2006/10/do-you-google.html |title=Do You "Google"? |last=Krantz |first=Michael |date=October 25, 2006 |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 17, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/ |title=To Google or Not to Google |last=Bylund |first=Anders |date=July 5, 2006 |website=msnbc.com |accessdate=February 17, 2010 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20060707062623/http://msnbc.msn.com/id/13720643/ |archivedate=July 7, 2006}}</ref> The first use of "Google" as a verb in [[pop culture]] happened on the TV series ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', in 2002.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Atlantic |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2014/06/the-first-use-of-the-verb-to-google-on-television-buffy-the-vampire-slayer/373599/ |title=The First Use of 'to Google' on Television? Buffy the Vampire Slayer |last=Meyer |first=Robinson |language=en-US|access-date=September 28, 2016}}</ref>

In 2005, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported on a 700 percent increase in third-quarter profit for Google, largely thanks to large companies shifting their advertising strategies from newspapers, magazines, and television to the Internet.<ref>{{cite news |first=David |last=Vise |title=Online Ads Give Google Huge Gain in Profit |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/10/20/AR2005102002058.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=October 21, 2005 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> In January 2008, all the data that passed through Google's MapReduce software component had an aggregated size of 20 [[petabyte]]s per day.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Jeffrey |last1=Dean |first2=Sanjay |last2=Ghemawat |title=MapReduce: simplified data processing on large clusters |url=http://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?doid=1327452.1327492 |website=ACM Digital Library |date=January 1, 2008 |accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Grzegorz |last=Czajkowski |title=Sorting 1PB with MapReduce |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2008/11/sorting-1pb-with-mapreduce.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=November 21, 2008 |accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Erick |last=Schonfeld |title=Google Processing 20,000 Terabytes A Day, And Growing |url=https://techcrunch.com/2008/01/09/google-processing-20000-terabytes-a-day-and-growing/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 9, 2008 |accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref> In 2009, a [[CNN]] report about top political searches of 2009 noted that "more than a billion searches" are being typed into Google on a daily basis.<ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Kuhn |title=Google unveils top political searches of 2009 |url=http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2009/12/18/google-unveils-top-political-searches-of-2009/ |website=[[CNN]] |date=December 18, 2009 |accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref> In May 2011, the number of monthly unique visitors to Google surpassed one billion for the first time, an 8.4&nbsp;percent increase from May 2010 (931&nbsp;million).<ref>{{cite web |author=Ben |title=Google's new record, 1 billion visitors in May |url=http://itsalltech.com/2011/06/22/googles-new-record-1-billion-visitors-in-may/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130116035631/http://itsalltech.com/2011/06/22/googles-new-record-1-billion-visitors-in-may/ |website=It's All Tech |date=June 2, 2011 |archivedate=January 16, 2013 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>

The year 2012 was the first time that Google generated $50 billion in annual revenue, generating $38 billion the previous year. In January 2013, then-CEO Larry Page commented, "We ended 2012 with a strong quarter ... Revenues were up 36% year-on-year, and 8% quarter-on-quarter. And we hit $50 billion in revenues for the first time last year – not a bad achievement in just a decade and a half."<ref>{{cite web |first=Seth |last=Fiegerman |title=Google Has Its First $50 Billion Year |url=http://mashable.com/2013/01/22/google-q4-earnings/#42cbeRCbSkqH |website=[[Mashable]] |date=January 22, 2013 |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>

In November 2018, Google announced its plan to expand its New York City office to a capacity of 12,000 employees.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-plans-large-new-york-city-expansion-1541636579|title=Google Plans Large New York City Expansion|last=Grant|first=Douglas MacMillan, Eliot Brown and Peter|work=WSJ|access-date=2018-11-08|language=en-US}}</ref>

=== 2013 onward ===
[[File:Logo Google 2013 Official.svg|thumb|200px|Google's logo until 2015]]
[[File:Google logo 2014.tiff|thumb|Screenshot of the Google homepage in 2015]]
Google announced the launch of a new company, called [[Calico (company)|Calico]], on September 19, 2013, to be led by [[Apple, Inc.]] chairman [[Arthur D. Levinson|Arthur Levinson]]. In the official public statement, Page explained that the "health and well-being" company would focus on "the challenge of ageing and associated diseases".<ref>{{cite news |title=Google spin-off Calico to search for answers to ageing |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24158924 |accessdate=September 20, 2013 |newspaper=BBC News |date=September 19, 2013 |author=Jane Wakefield}}</ref>

Google celebrated its 15-year anniversary on September 27, 2013, and in 2016 it celebrated its 18th birthday with an animated [[Doodle]] shown on web browsers around the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Google celebrates 18th birthday with a Doodle - amid some confusion over the correct date |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/09/26/when-is-googles-birthday/ |accessdate=September 27, 2016 |work=[[Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=Telegraph Media Group Limited}}</ref> although it has used other dates for its official birthday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/google-is-10-years-old-finding-the-real-google-birthday-12172 |website=searchengineland.com |title=Google Is 10 Years Old? Finding The Real Google Birthday |last=Sullivan |first=Danny |date=September 14, 2007 |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref> The reason for the choice of September 27 remains unclear, and a dispute with rival search engine [[Yahoo! Search]] in 2005 has been suggested as the cause.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Peterson |first=Andrea |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-switch/wp/2013/09/27/is-today-really-googles-birthday/ |title=Is today really Google's birthday? |newspaper=Washington Post |date=September 27, 2013 |accessdate=September 28, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Google celebrates 15th birthday with interactive piñata 'doodle' |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/google-celebrates-15th-birthday-with-interactive-piata-doodle-8842436.html |accessdate=September 28, 2013 |newspaper=The Independent |date=September 26, 2013 |author=John Hall |location=London}}</ref>

The [[Alliance for Affordable Internet]] (A4AI) was launched in October 2013; Google is part of the coalition of public and private organizations that also includes [[Facebook]], [[Intel]], and [[Microsoft]]. Led by [[Sir Tim Berners-Lee]], the A4AI seeks to make Internet access more affordable so that access is broadened in the developing world, where only 31% of people are online. Google will help to decrease Internet access prices so they fall below the UN Broadband Commission's worldwide target of 5% of monthly income.<ref>{{cite web |first=Samuel |last=Gibbs |title=Sir Tim Berners-Lee and Google lead coalition for cheaper internet |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/07/google-berners-lee-alliance-broadband-africa |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=October 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref>

The corporation's consolidated revenue for the third quarter of 2013 was reported in mid-October 2013 as $14.89 billion, a 12 percent increase compared to the previous quarter.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ryan |last=Whitwam |title=Google Beats Analyst Estimates For Third Quarter Results, Stock Passes $1000 Per Share |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2013/10/18/google-beats-analyst-estimates-for-third-quarter-results-stock-passes-1000-per-share/ |website=Android Police |date=October 18, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> Google's Internet business was responsible for $10.8 billion of this total, with an increase in the number of users' clicks on advertisements.<ref>{{cite news |title=Google earnings up 12% in third quarter even as Motorola losses deepen |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/17/google-q3-revenue-earnings-report|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131017221536/http://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/oct/17/google-q3-revenue-earnings-report|dead-url=yes|archive-date=October 17, 2013 |accessdate=October 18, 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=October 17, 2013 |author=Reuters}}</ref>

According to [[Interbrand]]'s annual Best Global Brands report, Google has been the second most valuable brand in the world (behind [[Apple Inc.]]) in 2013,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2013 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2013/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> 2014,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2014 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2014/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> 2015,<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2015 - Best Global Brands - Interbrand |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2015/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> and 2016, with a valuation of $133 billion.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rankings - 2016 - Best Global Brands |url=http://interbrand.com/best-brands/best-global-brands/2016/ranking/#?listFormat=ls |website=Interbrand |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref>

In September 2015, Google engineering manager Rachel Potvin revealed details about Google's software code at an engineering conference. She revealed that the entire Google codebase, which spans every single service it develops, consists of over 2 billion lines of code. All that code is stored in a code repository available to all 25,000 Google engineers, and the code is regularly copied and updated on 10 Google data centers. To keep control, Potvin said Google has built its own "version control system", called "Piper", and that "when you start a new project, you have a wealth of libraries already available to you. Almost everything has already been done." Engineers can make a single code change and deploy it on all services at the same time. The only major exceptions are that the PageRank search results algorithm is stored separately with only specific employee access, and the code for the Android operating system and the Google Chrome browser are also stored separately, as they don't run on the Internet. The "Piper" system spans 85 [[Terabyte|TB]] of data. Google engineers make 25,000 changes to the code each day and on a weekly basis change approximately 15 million lines of code across 250,000 files. With that much code, automated bots have to help. Potvin reported, "You need to make a concerted effort to maintain code health. And this is not just humans maintaining code health, but robots too.” Bots aren't writing code, but generating a lot of the data and configuration files needed to run the company's software. "Not only is the size of the repository increasing," Potvin explained, "but the rate of change is also increasing. This is an exponential curve."<ref>{{cite web |first=Cade |last=Metz |title=Google is 2 billion lines of code - and it's all in one place |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/09/google-2-billion-lines-codeand-one-place/ |website=Wired |date=September 16, 2015 |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Tarantola |title=Google's codebase is ludicrously huge for good reason |url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/09/18/googles-codebase-is-ludicrously-huge-for-good-reason/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=September 18, 2015 |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref>

{{As of|2016|10|post=,}} Google operates 70 offices in more than 40 countries.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google locations |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> [[Alexa Internet|Alexa]], a company that monitors commercial web traffic, lists Google.com as the most visited website in the world.<ref>{{cite web |title=google.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/google.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Several other Google services also figure in the top 100 most visited websites, including YouTube<ref>{{cite web |title=youtube.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/youtube.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> and Blogger.<ref>{{cite web |title=blogger.com Traffic Statistics |url=http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/blogger.com |website=[[Alexa Internet]] |date=November 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref>

=== Acquisitions and partnerships ===
{{Main|List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet}}
[[File:Google page brin.jpg|thumb|left|[[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] in 2003]]

==== 2000–2009 ====
In 2001, Google acquired [[Google Groups#Deja News|Deja News]], the operators of a large archive of materials from [[Usenet]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Google acquires Deja |url=http://www.geek.com/news/google-acquires-deja-544420/ |website=[[Geek.com]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=February 12, 2001 |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Drew |last=Cullen |title=Google saves Deja.com Usenet service |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2001/02/12/google_saves_deja_com_usenet/ |website=[[The Register]] |publisher=Situation Publishing |date=February 12, 2001 |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref> Google rebranded the archive as [[Google Groups]], and by the end of the year, it had expanded the history back to 1981.<ref>{{cite web |title=Digital history saved |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/1709527.stm |website=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=December 14, 2001 |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name="feeling-lucky-book">Edwards, D. (2011) [[I'm Feeling Lucky (book)|I'm Feeling Lucky: The Confessions of Google Employee Number 59]]. {{ISBN|978-0-547-41699-1}}</ref>

In April 2003, Google acquired [[AdSense#History|Applied Semantics]], a company specializing in making software applications for the online advertising space.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian |last=Morrissey |title=Today in History: Google Buys Applied Semantics |url=https://digiday.com/social/today-in-history-google-buys-applied-semantics/ |website=''[[Digiday]]'' |date=April 23, 2013 |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Bracetti |title=The 15 Most Important Tech Acquisitions of All Time |url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/01/the-15-most-important-tech-acquisitions-of-all-time/ |website=[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] |publisher=[[Verizon Hearst Media Partners]] |date=January 8, 2013 |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref> The [[AdSense]] contextual advertising technology developed by Applied Semantics was adopted into Google's advertising efforts.<ref>{{cite web |first=Danny |last=Sullivan |title=AdSense Turns 10: Reflections On Google's Great Leap Beyond Search Ads |url=http://marketingland.com/adsense-turns-10-reflections-on-googles-great-leap-34684 |website=Marketing Land |date=February 27, 2013 |accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref><ref name="feeling-lucky-book"/>

In 2004, Google acquired [[Keyhole, Inc]].<ref>{{Cite press release |title=Google Acquires Keyhole Corp |publisher=Google, Inc. |date=October 27, 2004 |url=https://www.google.com/press/pressrel/keyhole.html |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> Keyhole's [[eponym]]ous product was later renamed [[Google Earth]].

In April 2005, Google acquired [[Urchin (software)|Urchin Software]], using their Urchin on Demand product (along with ideas from Adaptive Path's Measure Map) to create [[Google Analytics]] in 2006.

In October 2006, Google announced that it had acquired the video-sharing site YouTube for $1.65&nbsp;billion in Google stock,<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Arrington |title=Google Has Acquired YouTube |url=https://techcrunch.com/2006/10/09/google-has-acquired-youtube/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=October 9, 2006 |accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Andrew Ross |last1=Sorkin |first2=Jeremy W. |last2=Peters |title=Google to Acquire YouTube for $1.65 Billion |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/10/09/business/09cnd-deal.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 9, 2006 |accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> and the deal was finalized on November 13, 2006.<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Arrington |title=Google Closes YouTube Acquisition |url=https://techcrunch.com/2006/11/13/google-closes-youtube-acquisition/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=November 13, 2006 |accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Eric |last=Auchard |title=Google closes YouTube deal |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-google-idUSWEN973120061114 |website=[[Reuters]] |publisher=[[Thomson Reuters]] |date=November 14, 2006 |accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref>

On April 13, 2007, Google reached an agreement to acquire [[DoubleClick]] for $3.1&nbsp;billion, transferring to Google valuable relationships that DoubleClick had with Web publishers and advertising agencies.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Louise |last1=Story |first2=Miguel |last2=Helft |title=Google Buys DoubleClick for $3.1 Billion |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/14/technology/14DoubleClick.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=April 14, 2007 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>
The deal was approved despite anti-trust concerns raised by competitors [[Microsoft]] and [[AT&T]].<ref>{{Cite book |title=Googled: The End of the World As We Know It |last=Auletta |first=Ken |date=2009 |publisher=The Penguin Press |isbn=9780753522431 |location=New York |language=English}}</ref>

In addition to the many companies Google has purchased, the firm has partnered with other organizations for research, advertising, and other activities. In 2005, Google partnered with [[NASA]] [[Ames Research Center]] to build {{convert|1000000|sqft|m2|-3}} of offices.<ref name="nasaames">{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/Can-Google-beat-the-new-office-curse/2100-1030_3-5884957.html |title=Can Google beat the new-office curse? |last=Mills |first=Elinor |date=September 29, 2005 |website=[[CNET]] |accessdate=February 26, 2010}}</ref>

In 2005 Google partnered with [[AOL]]<ref name="googleaol">{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/What-the-Google-AOL-deal-means-for-users/2100-1024_3-6010327.html |title=What the Google-AOL deal means for users |last=Mills |first=Elinor |date=December 28, 2005 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=February 26, 2010}}</ref> to enhance each other's [[video search]] services. In 2006 Google and [[Fox Sports Digital Media|Fox Interactive Media]] of [[News Corporation]] entered into a $900&nbsp;million agreement to provide search and advertising on the then-popular social networking site [[MySpace]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Fox Interactive Media Enters Into Landmark Agreement with Google Inc |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2006/08/fox-interactive-media-enters-into_07.html |website=News from Google |date=August 7, 2006 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>

In 2007, Google began sponsoring [[NORAD Tracks Santa]], displacing the former sponsor AOL. NORAD Tracks Santa purports to follow [[Santa Claus]]' progress on [[Christmas Eve]],<ref name="Tracking Santa: NORAD & Google Team Up For Christmas, December 1, 2007, Danny Sullivan">{{cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/tracking-santa-norad-google-team-up-for-christmas-12817 |title=Tracking Santa: NORAD & Google Team Up For Christmas, December 1, 2007, Danny Sullivan |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |website=Search Engine Land}}</ref> using Google Earth to "track Santa" in 3-D for the first time.<ref name="Behind the scenes: NORAD's Santa tracker for Thur, December 21, 2009 By Daniel Terdiman, CNET">{{cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-13772_3-10418101-52.html |title=Behind the scenes: NORAD's Santa tracker for Thur, December 21, 2009 By Daniel Terdiman, CNET |accessdate=December 31, 2009 |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]}}</ref><ref name="Instructions On Tracking Santa With NORAD & Google: The 2007 Edition, December 24, 2007, Danny Sullivan">{{cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/instructions-on-tracking-santa-with-norad-google-the-2007-edition-13001 |title=Instructions On Tracking Santa With NORAD & Google: The 2007 Edition, December 24, 2007, Danny Sullivan |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |website=Search Engine Land}}</ref>

In 2008, Google developed a partnership with [[GeoEye]] to launch a satellite providing Google with high-resolution (0.41&nbsp;m monochrome, 1.65&nbsp;m color) imagery for Google Earth. The satellite was launched from [[Vandenberg Air Force Base]] on September 6, 2008.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2008/09/06/us-geoeye-idUSN0633403420080906 |title=GeoEye launches high-resolution satellite |last=Shalal-Esa |first=Andrea |date=September 6, 2008 |work=Reuters |accessdate=February 26, 2010 |location=Washington}}</ref> Google also announced in 2008 that it was hosting an archive of ''[[Life (magazine)|Life Magazine]]''{{'}}s photographs.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Google gives online life to Life mag's photos |url=http://www.msnbc.msn.com/id/27802744/ |quote=Google Inc. has opened an online photo gallery that will include millions of images from ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine's archives that have never been seen by the public before |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 20, 2008 |accessdate=February 25, 2010 |location=Mountain View, California}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/google-to-host-10-million-time-life-unpublished-images-15513 |title=Google Hosting Time-Life Photo Archive, 10&nbsp;Million Unpublished Images Now Live |website=[[Search Engine Land]] |author=Greg Stirling |date=November 18, 2008 |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref>

==== 2010–present ====
In 2010, [[Google Energy]] made its first investment in a [[renewable energy]] project, putting $38.8&nbsp;million into two [[wind farm]]s in [[North Dakota]]. The company announced the two locations will generate 169.5&nbsp;megawatts of power, enough to supply 55,000 homes. The farms, which were developed by [[NextEra Energy Resources]], will reduce fossil fuel use in the region and return profits. NextEra Energy Resources sold Google a twenty-percent stake in the project to get funding for its development.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Google Invests in Two Wind Farms |first1=Scott |last1=Morrison |first2=Cassandra |last2=Sweet |newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=May 4, 2010 |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704342604575222420304732394 |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> In February 2010, the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]] FERC granted Google an authorization to buy and sell energy at market rates.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10456435-54.html |title=Google Energy can now buy and sell energy |work=Cnet.com}}</ref> The order specifically states that Google Energy—a subsidiary of Google—holds the rights "for the sale of energy, capacity, and ancillary services at market-based rates", but acknowledges that neither Google Energy nor its affiliates "own or control any generation or transmission" facilities.<ref>{{cite news |title=Google gets go-ahead to buy, sell energy |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-11128_3-10456435-54.html |work=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=September 23, 2013 |author=Candace Lombardi |date=February 19, 2010}}</ref> The corporation exercised this authorization in September 2013 when it announced it would purchase all the electricity produced by the not-yet-built 240-megawatt Happy Hereford wind farm.<ref>{{cite news |title=Google is on the way to quietly becoming an electric utility |url=http://qz.com/125407/google-is-on-the-way-to-quietly-becoming-an-electric-utility/ |accessdate=September 23, 2013 |newspaper=Quartz |date=September 18, 2013 |author=Todd Woody}}</ref>

Also in 2010, Google purchased [[Global IP Solutions]], a Norway-based company that provides web-based [[teleconferencing]] and other related services. This acquisition enabled Google to add telephone-style services to its list of products.<ref>{{Cite news |last1=Gomes |first1=Lee |date=May 18, 2010 |title=Google's Latest Telephony Play |work=[[Forbes]] |url=https://www.forbes.com/2010/05/18/google-microsoft-videoconferencing-technology-telephony.html |accessdate=November 27, 2010}}</ref> On May 27, 2010, Google announced it had also closed the acquisition of the mobile ad network [[AdMob]]. This occurred days after the [[Federal Trade Commission]] closed its investigation into the purchase.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.appscout.com/2010/05/google_closes_acquisition_of_a.php |title=Google Closes Acquisition of AdMob |last1=Albanesius |first1=Chloe |date=May 27, 2010 |website=AppScout |accessdate=June 16, 2010}}</ref> Google acquired the company for an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2355609,00.asp |title=Google Acquires Mobile Display Ad Firm AdMob |last1=Albanesius |first1=Chloe |date=November 9, 2010 |work=PC Magazine |publisher=Ziff Davis Publishing Holdings Inc. |accessdate=June 16, 2010}}</ref> In July 2010, Google signed an agreement with an Iowa wind farm to buy 114 megawatts of energy for 20 years.<ref name="wind energy">{{cite web |url=http://news.techworld.com/green-it/3232690/google-buys-power-from-iowa-wind-farm/?olo=rss |title=Google buys power from Iowa wind farm |website=News.techworld.com |date=July 21, 2010 |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref>

On April 4, 2011, ''[[The Globe and Mail]]'' reported that Google bid $900&nbsp;million for 6000 [[Nortel Networks]] patents.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/google-bids-900-million-for-nortel-patents/article1969788/ |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110407100606/http://www.theglobeandmail.com/report-on-business/google-bids-900-million-for-nortel-patents/article1969788/ |archivedate=April 7, 2011 |title=Bid for Nortel patents marks Google's new push into mobile world |work=Globe and Mail |date=April 4, 2011 |accessdate=April 25, 2011 |location=Toronto}}</ref>

On August 15, 2011, Google made its largest-ever acquisition to date when it announced that it would acquire [[Motorola Mobility]] for $12.5&nbsp;billion<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/faster-forward/post/google-agrees-to-acquire-motorola-mobility/2011/08/15/gIQABmTkGJ_blog.html |title=Google agrees to acquire Motorola Mobility |author=Tsukayama, Hayley |work=The Washington Post |date=August 15, 2011 |accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://investor.google.com/releases/2011/0815.html |title=Google to Acquire Motorola Mobility&nbsp;— Google Investor Relations |website=Google |accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> subject to approval from regulators in the United States and Europe. In a post on Google's blog, Google Chief Executive and co-founder Larry Page revealed that the acquisition was a strategic move to strengthen Google's patent portfolio. The company's Android operating system has come under fire in an industry-wide patent battle, as Apple and Microsoft have sued Android device makers such as HTC, Samsung, and Motorola.<ref name="appleinsider1">{{cite web |last=Hughes |first=Neil |url=http://www.appleinsider.com/articles/11/08/15/google_ceo_anticompetitive_apple_microsoft_forced_motorola_deal.html |title=Google CEO: 'Anticompetitive' Apple, Microsoft forced Motorola deal |website=AppleInsider |accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> The merger was completed on May 22, 2012, after the approval of [[China]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-18164190 |title=Google |accessdate=May 23, 2012 |work=BBC News |date=May 22, 2012}}</ref>

This purchase was made in part to help Google gain Motorola's considerable patent portfolio on mobile phones and wireless technologies, to help protect Google in its ongoing patent disputes with other companies,<ref name="supercharging android">{{cite web |last=Page |first=Larry |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2011/08/supercharging-android-google-to-acquire.html |title=Official Google Blog: Supercharging Android: Google to Acquire Motorola Mobility |website=Google Blog at Blogspot.com |accessdate=August 17, 2011}}</ref> mainly [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] and [[Microsoft]],<ref name="appleinsider1"/> and to allow it to continue to freely offer [[Android (operating system)|Android]].<ref name="cnet">{{cite web |title=Google to buy Motorola Mobility for $12.5B |url=http://news.cnet.com/8301-1035_3-20092362-94/google-to-buy-motorola-mobility-for-$12.5b/ |first=Roger |last=Cheng |date=August 15, 2011 |website=CNet News}}</ref> After the acquisition closed, Google began to restructure the Motorola business to fit Google's strategy. On August 13, 2012, Google announced plans to lay off 4000 Motorola Mobility employees.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/08/13/us-motorolamobility-jobs-idUSBRE87C07F20120813 |title=Google to cut 4,000 Motorola Mobility jobs, shares rise |date=August 13, 2012 |work=Reuters}}</ref> On December 10, 2012, Google sold the manufacturing operations of Motorola Mobility to [[Flextronics]] for $75&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |first=Daniel |last=Cooper |title=Motorola's retreat continues, sells factories in China and Brazil to Flextronics for $75 million |url=https://www.engadget.com/2012/12/11/motorola-flextronics/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 11, 2012 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> As a part of the agreement, Flextronics will manufacture undisclosed Android and other mobile devices.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.zdnet.com/cn/flextronics-acquires-motorola-mobilitys-plants-in-china-brazil-7000008603/ |title=Flextronics acquires Motorola Mobility's plants in China, Brazil |work=ZDNet |date=December 11, 2012}}</ref> On December 19, 2012, Google sold the Motorola Home business division of Motorola Mobility to [[Arris Group]] for $2.35&nbsp;billion in a cash-and-stock transaction. As a part of this deal, Google acquired a 15.7% stake in Arris Group valued at $300&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Seifert |title=Google sells Motorola Home set top box division to Arris for $2.35 billion |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/12/19/3786086/google-sells-motorola-home-to-arris-for-2-35-billion-in-cash-and-stock |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=December 19, 2012 |accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Motorola Home Finds A New Home At Arris. Google Sells Broadband Unit For $2.35B To Double Down On Mobile |url=https://techcrunch.com/2012/12/19/motorola-home-finds-a-new-home-at-arris-google-sells-broadband-unit-for-2-35b-to-double-down-on-mobile/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 19, 2012 |accessdate=April 7, 2017}}</ref>

In June 2013, Google acquired [[Waze]], a $966 million deal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dara |last=Kerr |title=Google reveals it spent $966 million in Waze acquisition |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-reveals-it-spent-966-million-in-waze-acquisition/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=July 25, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> While Waze would remain an independent entity, its social features, such as its crowdsourced location platform, were reportedly valuable integrations between Waze and [[Google Maps]], Google's own mapping service.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ingrid |last=Lunden |title=Google Bought Waze For $1.1B, Giving A Social Data Boost To Its Mapping Business |url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/06/11/its-official-google-buys-waze-giving-a-social-data-boost-to-its-location-and-mapping-business/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 11, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref>

[[File:Google-Deep Mind headquarters in London, 6 Pancras Square.jpg|thumb|Entrance of building where Google and its subsidiary Deep Mind are located at 6 Pancras Square, London, UK.]]
On January 26, 2014, Google announced it had agreed to acquire [[DeepMind Technologies]], a privately held artificial intelligence company from [[London]]. DeepMind describes itself as having the ability to combine the best techniques from machine learning and systems neuroscience to build general-purpose learning algorithms. DeepMind's first commercial applications were used in simulations, e-commerce and games. {{As of|2013|12|post=,}} it was reported that DeepMind had roughly 75 employees.<ref name=Chowdhry-DeepMind>{{cite news |last=Chowdhry |first=Amit |title=Google To Acquire Artificial Intelligence Company DeepMind |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/amitchowdhry/2014/01/27/google-to-acquire-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind/ |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=Forbes |date=January 27, 2014}}</ref> Technology news website ''[[Recode]]'' reported that the company was purchased for $400 million though it was not disclosed where the information came from. A Google spokesman would not comment of the price.<ref name="Helgren- DeepMind">{{cite news |last=Helgren |first=Chris |title=Google to buy artificial intelligence company DeepMind |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/01/27/us-google-deepmind-idUSBREA0Q03220140127 |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=Reuters |date=January 27, 2014}}</ref><ref name="Ribeiro- DeepMind">{{cite news |last=Ribeiro |first=Jon |title=Google buys artificial intelligence company DeepMind |url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2091500/google-acquires-artificial-intelligence-company-deepmind.html |accessdate=January 27, 2014 |newspaper=PC World |date=January 27, 2014}}</ref> The purchase of DeepMind aids in Google's recent growth in the artificial intelligence and robotics community.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kwame |last=Opam |title=Google buying AI startup DeepMind for a reported $400 million |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/1/26/5348640/google-deepmind-acquisition-robotics-ai |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=January 26, 2014 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

On January 29, 2014, Google announced that it would divest Motorola Mobility to [[Lenovo]] for $2.91 billion, a fraction of the original $12.5 billion price paid by Google to acquire the company. Google retained all but 2000 of Motorola's patents and entered into cross-licensing deals.<ref name="Opan- DeepMind- Post">{{cite news |title=Google sells Motorola Mobility to Lenovo for $2.91 billion |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/technology/google-sells-motorola-mobility-to-lenovo-for-291-billion/2014/01/29/92836bce-8932-11e3-833c-33098f9e5267_story.html |accessdate=January 30, 2014 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=January 30, 2014 |first=Cecilia |last=Kang}}</ref>

On September 21, 2017, [[HTC]] announced a "cooperation agreement" in which it would sell non-exclusive rights to certain intellectual property, as well as smartphone talent, to Google for $1.1 billion.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/20/google-htc-sign-cooperation-agreement.html |title=Google agrees to buy part of HTC for $1.1 billion |last=Balakrishnan |first=Saheli Roy Choudhury, Anita |date=September 20, 2017 |work=CNBC|access-date=September 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/9/20/16340108/google-htc-smartphone-team-acquisition-announced |title=Google is buying part of HTC’s smartphone team for $1.1 billion |work=The Verge|access-date=September 21, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.blog.google/topics/hardware/google-signs-agreement-htc-continuing-our-big-bet-hardware/ |title=Google signs agreement with HTC, continuing our big bet on hardware |date=September 21, 2017 |work=Google|access-date=September 21, 2017 |language=en}}</ref>

On December 6, 2017, Google made its first investment in [[India]] and picked up a significant minority stake in hyper-local concierge and delivery player Dunzo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/small-biz/startups/newsbuzz/google-makes-first-direct-investment-in-india-funds-hyper-local-startup-dunzo/articleshow/61925929.cms|title=Google makes first direct investment in India, funds hyper local startup Dunzo|last=Chanchani|first=Madhav|date=December 9, 2017|work=The Economic Times|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> The Benguluru-based startup received $12 million investment in Google's series B funding round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/technology/internet/google-first-direct-investment-indian-startup-bangaluru-dunzo-12-million-usd/story/265379.html|title=Google invests Rs 65 crore in hyper local app Dunzo, its first direct investment in an Indian startup|website=www.businesstoday.in|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref>

On March 29, 2018, Google led a Series C funding round into online-to-offline fashion e-commerce start-up Fynd.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://tech.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/startups/google-backs-o2o-fashion-commerce-platform-fynd/63529124|title=Google backs O2O fashion commerce platform Fynd - ETtech|last=www.ETtech.com|website=ETtech.com|language=en|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> It was its second direct investment in India with an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/business/Industry/online-fashion-firm-fynd-secures-funding-round-led-by-google/article23383121.ece|title=Online fashion firm Fynd secures funding round led by Google|last=Vijayakumar|first=Sanjay|date=March 29, 2018|work=The Hindu|access-date=June 6, 2018|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/venture-capital/google-invests-in-o2o-e-commerce-startup-fynd/articleshow/63531033.cms|title=Google invests in O2O e-commerce startup Fynd - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=June 6, 2018}}</ref> In this way, Google is also looking to build an ecosystem in India across high-frequency hyper-local transactions as well as in the healthcare, financial services, and education sectors.

On August 23, 2018, Google deleted 39 [[YouTube]] accounts, 13 [[Google+]] accounts and 6 blogs on [[Blogger (service)|Blogger]] due to their engagement in politically motivated phishing, the deleted accounts were found to be tied with [[Islamic Republic of Iran Broadcasting|Islamic Republic of Iran Broadcasting (IRIB)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/08/23/google-deletes-58-accounts-with-ties-to-iran-from-youtube-and-other-sites.html|title=Google deletes 58 accounts with ties to Iran from YouTube and other sites|last=Salinas|first=Sara|date=August 23, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=August 27, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/23/technology/google-youtube-iranian-influence.html|title=Google Deletes 39 YouTube Channels Linked to Iranian Influence Operation|access-date=August 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/8/23/17775538/google-youtube-iran-russia-election-interference-influence-campaign|title=Google took down 39 YouTube channels linked to Iranian influence campaign|work=The Verge|access-date=August 27, 2018}}</ref>

===Google data centers===
{{see also|Google data centers}}
[[Google data centers]] are located in North and South America, Asia, Europe.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/about/datacenters/inside/locations/index.html|title=Data center locations|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517162154/https://www.google.com/about/datacenters/inside/locations/index.html|archive-date=May 17, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref>

Traditionally, Google relied on [[parallel computing]] on commodity hardware<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=May 26, 2018|title=Google's Secret: 'Cheap and Fast' Hardware|url=https://research.google.com/archive/googlecluster-ieee.pdf|website=PCWorld|date=October 10, 2003}}</ref> like mainstream x86 computers similar to home PCs<ref>{{cite journal|first1=L.A.|last1=Barroso|first2=J.|last2=Dean|first3=U.|last3=Holzle|title=Web search for a planet: the google cluster architecture|journal=IEEE Micro|date=April 29, 2003|issn=0272-1732|pages=22–28|volume=23|issue=2|doi=10.1109/mm.2003.1196112|quote=We believe that the best price/performance tradeoff for our applications comes from fashioning a reliable computing infrastructure from clusters of unreliable commodity PCs.}}</ref> to keep costs per query low.<ref name=CNET2009>{{cite news|accessdate=May 26, 2018|title=Google uncloaks once-secret server|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-uncloaks-once-secret-server-10209580/|newspaper=CNET|date=April 1, 2009|quote=Mainstream servers with x86 processors were the only option, he added. "Ten years ago...it was clear the only way to make (search) work as free product was to run on relatively cheap hardware. You can't run it on a [[mainframe server|mainframe]]. The margins just don't work out," he said.}}</ref> In 2005, it started developing its own designs, which were only revealed in 2009.<ref name=CNET2009/>

In October 2013, ''[[The Washington Post]]'' reported that the U.S. [[National Security Agency]] intercepted communications between Google's data centers, as part of a program named [[Muscular (surveillance program)|MUSCULAR]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/national-security/nsa-infiltrates-links-to-yahoo-google-data-centers-worldwide-snowden-documents-say/2013/10/30/e51d661e-4166-11e3-8b74-d89d714ca4dd_story.html |title=NSA infiltrates links to Yahoo, Google data centers worldwide, Snowden documents say |first1=Barton |last1=Gellman |first2=Ashkan |last2=Soltani |work=The Washington Post |date=October 30, 2013 |accessdate=November 1, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Charlie |last1=Savage |first2=Claire Cain |last2=Miller |first3=Nicole |last3=Perlroth |title=N.S.A. Said to Tap Google and Yahoo Abroad |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/31/technology/nsa-is-mining-google-and-yahoo-abroad.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 30, 2013 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> This wiretapping was made possible because Google did not encrypt data passed inside its own network.<ref>{{cite web |first=Sean |last=Gallagher |title=How the NSA's MUSCULAR tapped Google's and Yahoo's private networks |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2013/10/how-the-nsas-muscular-tapped-googles-and-yahoos-private-networks/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Condé Nast]] |date=October 31, 2013 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> Google began encrypting data sent between data centers in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |first=Claire Cain |last=Miller |title=Angry Over U.S. Surveillance, Tech Giants Bolster Defenses |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/11/01/technology/angry-over-us-surveillance-tech-giants-bolster-defenses.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 31, 2013 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

Google's most efficient data center runs at {{convert|35|C}} using only fresh air cooling, requiring no electrically powered air conditioning; the servers run so hot that humans cannot go near them for extended periods.<ref>{{cite web|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160613112324/http://www.geek.com/chips/googles-most-efficient-data-center-runs-at-95-degrees-1478473/|archive-date=June 13, 2016 |url=http://www.geek.com/chips/googles-most-efficient-data-center-runs-at-95-degrees-1478473/ |title=Google's most efficient data center runs at 95 degrees |website=geek.com |date=March 27, 2012 |author=Matthew Humphries |accessdate=June 13, 2016}}</ref>

An August 2011 report estimated that Google had about 900,000 servers in their data centers, based on energy usage. The report does state that "Google never says how many servers are running in its data centers."<ref>{{cite web |first=Rich |last=Miller |title=Report: Google Uses About 900,000 Servers |url=http://www.datacenterknowledge.com/archives/2011/08/01/report-google-uses-about-900000-servers/ |publisher=Data Center Knowledge |date=August 1, 2011 |accessdate=December 6, 2016}}</ref>

In December 2016, Google announced that—starting in 2017—it will power all of its data centers, as well as all of its offices, from 100% renewable energy. The commitment will make Google "the world's largest corporate buyer of renewable power, with commitments reaching 2.6 gigawatts (2,600 megawatts) of wind and solar energy". Google also stated that it does not count that as its final goal; it says that "since the wind doesn't blow 24 hours a day, we'll also broaden our purchases to a variety of energy sources that can enable renewable power, every hour of every day". Additionally, the project will "help support communities" around the world, as the purchase commitments will "result in infrastructure investments of more than $3.5 billion globally", and will "generate tens of millions of dollars per year in revenue to local property owners, and tens of millions more to local and national governments in tax revenue".<ref>{{cite web |first=Urs |last=Hölzle |title=We're set to reach 100% renewable energy — and it's just the beginning |url=https://blog.google/topics/environment/100-percent-renewable-energy/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |date=December 6, 2016 |accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Statt |title=Google just notched a big victory in the fight against climate change |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/12/6/13852004/google-data-center-oklahoma-renewable-energy-climate-change |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=December 6, 2016 |accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Darrell |last=Etherington |title=Google says it will hit 100% renewable energy by 2017 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/06/google-says-it-will-hit-100-renewable-energy-by-2017/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 7, 2016 |accessdate=December 8, 2016}}</ref>

===Alphabet===
{{Main|Alphabet Inc.}}
On August 10, 2015, Google announced plans to reorganize its various interests as a [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] called [[Alphabet Inc.|Alphabet]]. Google became Alphabet's leading subsidiary, and will continue to be the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet interests. Upon completion of the restructure, [[Sundar Pichai]] became CEO of Google, replacing [[Larry Page]], who became CEO of Alphabet.<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian |last=Womack |title=Google Rises After Creating Holding Company Called Alphabet |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-10/google-to-adopt-new-holding-structure-under-name-alphabet- |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=August 10, 2015 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first1=Alistair |last1=Barr |first2=Rolf |last2=Winkler |title=Google Creates Parent Company Called Alphabet in Restructuring |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-creates-new-company-alphabet-1439240645 |publisher=''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' |date=August 10, 2015 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Conor |last=Dougherty |title=Google to Reorganize as Alphabet to Keep Its Lead as an Innovator |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/technology/google-alphabet-restructuring.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=August 10, 2015 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref>

On September 1, 2017, Google Inc. announced its plans of restructuring as a [[limited liability company]], Google LLC, as a wholly owned subsidiary of XXVI Holdings Inc., which is formed as a subsidiary of Alphabet Inc. to hold the equity of its other subsidiaries, including Google LLC and other bets.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-01/alphabet-wraps-up-reorganization-with-a-new-company-called-xxvi |title=Alphabet Finishes Reorganization With New XXVI Company |date=September 1, 2017 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |accessdate=September 2, 2017}}</ref>

== Products and services ==
{{See also|List of Google products}}

=== Advertising ===
[[File:Ad-tech London 2010 (2).JPG|thumb|Google on ad-tech London, 2010]]

As per its 2017 Annual report, Google generates most of its revenues from advertising. This includes sales of apps, purchases made in-app, digital content products on google and you tube, android and licensing and service fees, including fees received for Google Cloud offerings. 46% of this was from clicks (cost per clicks), amounting to US$ 109,652 million in 2017. This includes three principal methods, namely [[AdMob]], [[AdSense]] (such as AdSense for Content, [[AdSense]] for Search, etc.) and DoubleClick AdExchange.<ref name="agm2017">{{cite book |title=Annualg report (Alphabet Inc.) - 2017 |date=1 March 2018 |publisher=Alphabet Inc. Investor relations |url=https://abc.xyz/investor |accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref> 

For the 2006 fiscal year, the company reported $10.492{{nbsp}}billion in total advertising revenues and only $112{{nbsp}}million in licensing and other revenues.<ref name="10-K">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1288776/000119312507044494/d10k.htm |title=Form 10-K{{nbsp}}– Annual Report |accessdate=July 5, 2010 |publisher=SEC}}</ref> In 2011, 96% of Google's revenue was derived from its advertising programs.<ref name="Google-Inc-Jan-2012-10-K">{{cite web |url=http://pdf.secdatabase.com/44/0001193125-12-025336.pdf |title=Google Inc, Form 10-K, Annual Report, Filing Date January 26, 2012 |publisher=secdatabase.com |accessdate=March 8, 2013}}</ref> In addition to its own algorithms for understanding search requests, Google uses technology from the company [[DoubleClick]], to project user interest and target advertising to the search context and the user history.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Nakashima, Ellen |title=Some Web Firms Say They Track Behavior Without Explicit Consent |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/08/11/AR2008081102270_pf.html |date=August 12, 2008 |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Miguel |last=Helft |title=Google to Offer Ads Based on Interests |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/03/11/technology/internet/11google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=March 11, 2009 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

In 2007, Google launched "[[AdSense for Mobile]]", taking advantage of the emerging mobile advertising market.<ref name="adsense_mobile">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/press/annc/20070917_mobileads.html |title=Google AdSense for Mobile unlocks the potential of the mobile advertising market |date=September 17, 2007 |website=Google, Inc. |accessdate=February 26, 2010}}</ref>

[[Google Analytics]] allows website owners to track where and how people use their website, for example by examining click rates for all the links on a page.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Bright |title=Surfing on the sly with IE8's new "InPrivate" Internet |url=https://arstechnica.com/information-technology/2008/08/surfing-on-the-sly-ie8s-inprivate-internet/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Condé Nast]] |date=August 27, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> Google advertisements can be placed on third-party websites in a two-part program. Google's [[AdWords]] allows advertisers to display their advertisements in the Google content network, through a cost-per-click scheme.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vangie |last=Beal |title=AdWords - Google AdWords |url=http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adwords.html |website=Webopedia |publisher=QuinStreet Inc. |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref> The sister service, Google [[AdSense]], allows website owners to display these advertisements on their website and earn money every time ads are clicked.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vangie |last=Beal |title=AdSense - Google AdSense |url=http://www.webopedia.com/TERM/A/adsense.html |website=Webopedia |publisher=QuinStreet Inc. |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref>

One of the criticisms of this program is the possibility of [[click fraud]], which occurs when a person or automated script clicks on advertisements without being interested in the product, causing the advertiser to pay money to Google unduly. Industry reports in 2006 claimed that approximately 14 to 20&nbsp; percent of clicks were fraudulent or invalid.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mills |first=Elinor |url=http://news.cnet.com/Google-to-offer-advertisers-click-fraud-stats/2100-1024_3-6098469.html |title=Google to offer advertisers click fraud stats |work=news.cnet.com |publisher=CNET |date=July 25, 2006 |accessdate=July 29, 2006}}</ref>

In February 2003, Google stopped showing the advertisements of [[Oceana (non-profit group)|Oceana]], a non-profit organization protesting a major cruise ship's sewage treatment practices. Google cited its editorial policy at the time, stating "Google does not accept advertising if the ad or site advocates against other individuals, groups, or organizations."<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.webpronews.com/topnews/2004/05/17/google-somewhat-lifts-oceana-ad-ban |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090130095413/http://www.webpronews.com/topnews/2004/05/17/google-somewhat-lifts-oceana-ad-ban |archivedate=January 30, 2009 |title=Google Somewhat Lifts Oceana Ad Ban |publisher=webpronews.com}}</ref> In June 2008, Google reached an advertising agreement with Yahoo!, which would have allowed Yahoo! to feature Google advertisements on its web pages. The alliance between the two companies was never completely realized because of [[Competition law|antitrust]] concerns by the [[United States Department of Justice|U.S. Department of Justice]]. As a result, Google pulled out of the deal in November 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bloggingstocks.com/2008/10/31/yahoo-and-google-may-dump-their-deal/print/ |title=Yahoo and Google may dump their deal |last=Mclntyre |first=Douglas |publisher=Bloggingstocks.com |date=October 31, 2008 |accessdate=October 26, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2008/11/ending-our-agreement-with-yahoo.html |title=Ending our agreement with Yahoo! |last=Drummond |first=David |date=November 5, 2008 |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |publisher=Google, Inc}}</ref>

In July 2016, Google started rejecting all flash-based adverts replacing them by HTML5. Google's plan was to go “100% HTML5” beginning on January 2, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://latestgadgets.tech/2016/02/11/google-will-reject-flash-based-adverts-push-html5/|title=Google Will Reject All Flash Based Adverts In a Push For HTML5 • Latest Gadgets|date=February 11, 2016|work=Latest Gadgets|access-date=June 13, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Search engine ===
{{Main|Google Search|Google Images}}
[[File:Google web search.png|thumb|left|upright=1.15|Google Search homepage {{as of|2016|12|2|df=|lc=y}}]]

According to [[comScore]] market research from November 2009, [[Google Search]] is the dominant search engine in the United States market, with a [[market share]] of 65.6%.<ref name="comscore">{{Cite news |date=December 16, 2006 |title=comScore Releases November 2009 U.S. Search Engine Rankings |url=http://www.comscore.com/Press_Events/Press_Releases/2009/12/comScore_Releases_November_2009_U.S._Search_Engine_Rankings |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> Google [[search engine indexing|indexes]] billions of web pages to allow users to search for the information they desire through the use of keywords and [[Operator (computer programming)|operators]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Michael |last=Arrington |title=Google's Misleading Blog Post: The Size Of The Web And The Size Of Their Index Are Very Different |url=https://techcrunch.com/2008/07/25/googles-misleading-blog-post-on-the-size-of-the-web/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=July 25, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

In 2003, ''[[The New York Times]]'' complained about Google's [[search engine indexing|indexing]], claiming that Google's [[web cache|caching]] of content on its site infringed its copyright for the content.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.cnet.com/2100-1038_3-1024234.html |title=Google cache raises copyright concerns |last1=Olsen |first1=Stefanie |date=July 9, 2003 |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=June 13, 2010}}</ref> In both ''[[Field v. Google]]'' and ''Parker v. Google'', the United States District Court of [[Nevada]] ruled in favor of Google.<ref>{{Cite court |litigants=Field v. Google |opinion=CV-S-04-0413-RCJ-LRL |court=Nevada [[United States district court|District Court]] |date=January 19, 2006 |url=https://www.eff.org/IP/blake_v_google/google_nevada_order.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929110547/http://www.eff.org/IP/blake_v_google/google_nevada_order.pdf |archivedate=September 29, 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite court |litigants=Parker v. Google |opinion=04-CV-3918 |court=[[United States district court|Eastern Pennsylvania District Court]] |date=March 10, 2006 |url=http://www.paed.uscourts.gov/documents/opinions/06D0306P.pdf |quote=}}</ref> The publication ''[[2600: The Hacker Quarterly]]'' has compiled a list of words that google's new [[Google Instant|instant search feature]] will not search.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/09/29/google-instant-censorship_n_743203.html |title=Google Instant Censorship: The Strangest Terms Blacklisted By Google |work=The Huffington Post |date=September 29, 2010 |accessdate=October 26, 2010 |first=Bianca |last=Bosker}}</ref>

Google also hosts [[Google Books]]. The company began scanning books and uploading limited previews, and full books were allowed, into its new book search engine. The [[Authors Guild]], a group that represents 8,000 U.S. authors, filed a class action suit in a New York City federal court against Google in 2005 over this service. Google replied that it is in compliance with all existing and historical applications of copyright laws regarding books.<ref>{{cite web |first=China |last=Martin |url=http://www.infoworld.com/t/platforms/google-hit-second-lawsuit-over-library-project-722 |title=Google hit with second lawsuit over Library project |publisher=[[InfoWorld]] |date=November 26, 2007}}</ref> Google eventually reached a revised settlement in 2009 to limit its scans to books from the U.S., the UK, Australia, and Canada.<ref>{{Cite news |author=Pettersson, Edvard |title=Google Wins Preliminary Approval of Online Books Settlement |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=ahUxORgasDFs |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67Qvo6uhf?url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=ahUxORgasDFs |archivedate=May 5, 2012 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=November 20, 2009 |accessdate=December 18, 2009 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> Furthermore, the Paris Civil Court ruled against Google in late 2009, asking it to remove the works of La Martinière ([[Éditions du Seuil]]) from its database.<ref name=Smith>{{Cite news |author=Smith, Heather |title=Google's French Book Scanning Project Halted by Court |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=apZ3UG9CPLo8 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/67QvoTecZ?url=http://www.bloomberg.com/apps/news?pid=newsarchive&sid=apZ3UG9CPLo8 |archivedate=May 5, 2012 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=December 18, 2009 |accessdate=December 18, 2009 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref> In competition with [[Amazon.com]], Google sells digital versions of new books.<ref>{{cite web |first=Motoko |last=Rich |title=Preparing to Sell E-Books, Google Takes on Amazon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/01/technology/internet/01google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 31, 2009 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

On July 21, 2010, in response to [[Bing (search engine)|Bing]], Google updated its image search to display a streaming sequence of [[thumbnail]]s that enlarge when pointed at. Although web searches still appear in a batch per page format, on July 23, 2010, dictionary definitions for certain English words began appearing above the linked results for web searches.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/07/this-week-in-search-72510.html |title=This Week in Search 7/25/10 |last1=Mayer |first1=Marissa |publisher=Google, Inc. |date=July 25, 2010 |accessdate=July 28, 2010}}</ref>

The "Hummingbird" update to the Google search engine was announced in September 2013. The update was introduced over the month prior to the announcement and allows users ask the search engine a question in natural language rather than entering keywords into the search box.<ref>{{cite news |title=Google introduces the biggest algorithm change in three years |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2013/sep/27/google-biggest-algorithm-change-hummingbird |accessdate=September 29, 2013 |newspaper=Guardian |date=September 27, 2013 |author=Samuel Gibbs}}</ref>

In August 2016, Google announced two major changes to its mobile search results. The first change removes the "mobile-friendly" label that highlighted easy to read pages from its mobile search results page. For the second change, the company—starting on January 10, 2017—will punish mobile pages that show intrusive [[interstitial ad]]vertisements when a user first opens a page. Such pages will also rank lower in Google search results.<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google will soon start punishing mobile sites that show hard-to-dismiss popups |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/08/23/good-riddance/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=August 23, 2016 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

In May 2017, Google enabled a new "Personal" tab in Google Search, letting users search for content in their Google accounts' various services, including email messages from [[Gmail]] and photos from [[Google Photos]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Barry |last=Schwartz |title=Google Adds Personal Tab To Search Filters |url=https://www.seroundtable.com/google-personal-tab-search-23912.html |website=Search Engine Roundtable |publisher=RustyBrick |date=May 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Chaim |last=Gartenberg |title=Google adds new Personal tab to search results to show Gmail and Photos content |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/26/15701778/google-personal-tab-search-results-gmail-photos-images-maps-news-filter |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=May 26, 2017 |accessdate=May 27, 2017}}</ref>

=== Enterprise services{{anchor|Enterprise_products}} ===
{{Main|G Suite}}
[[G Suite]] is a monthly subscription offering for organizations and businesses to get access to a collection of Google's services, including [[Gmail]], [[Google Drive]] and [[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets]] and [[Google Slides]], with additional administrative tools, unique domain names, and 24/7 support.<ref>{{cite web |title=Choose a Plan |url=https://gsuite.google.com/intl/en_ie/pricing.html |website=G Suite by Google Cloud |accessdate=December 2, 2016}}</ref>

[[File:Google Appliance.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|Google's search appliance at the 2008 [[RSA Conference]]|alt=Google's search appliance]]
[[Google Search Appliance]] was launched in February 2002, targeted toward providing search technology for larger organizations.<ref name="milestones"/> Google launched the [[Google Mini|Mini]] three years later, which was targeted at smaller organizations. Late in 2006, Google began to sell Custom Search Business Edition, providing customers with an advertising-free window into Google.com's index. The service was renamed Google Site Search in 2008.<ref name="csbe2gss">{{cite web |url=http://searchengineland.com/google-rebrands-custom-search-business-edition-as-google-site-search-14123 |title=Google Rebrands Custom Search "Business Edition" As "Google Site Search" |last1=Sterling |first1=Greg |date=June 3, 2008 |publisher=Search Engine Land |accessdate=June 16, 2010}}</ref> Site Search customers were notified by email in late March 2017 that no new licenses for Site Search would be sold after April 1, 2017, but that customer and technical support would be provided for the duration of existing license agreements.<ref>{{cite web |first=Barb |last=Darrow |title=Google Plans To Discontinue Yet Another Product |url=http://fortune.com/2017/02/21/google-site-search-discontinued/ |website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |publisher=[[Time Inc.]] |date=February 21, 2017 |accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Abner |last=Li |title=Google reportedly discontinuing paid Site Search in favor of ad-supported version |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/02/21/google-site-search-discontinued/ |website=9to5Google |date=February 21, 2017 |accessdate=March 27, 2017}}</ref>

On March 15, 2016, Google announced the introduction of Google Analytics 360 Suite, "a set of integrated data and marketing analytics products, designed specifically for the needs of enterprise-class marketers" which can be integrated with [[BigQuery]] on the Google Cloud Platform. Among other things, the suite is designed to help "enterprise class marketers" "see the complete customer journey", generate "useful insights", and "deliver engaging experiences to the right people".<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul |last=Muret |title=Introducing the Google Analytics 360 Suite |url=https://analytics.googleblog.com/2016/03/introducing-google-analytics-360-suite.html |date=March 15, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref> Jack Marshall of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote that the suite competes with existing marketing cloud offerings by companies including [[Adobe Systems|Adobe]], [[Oracle Corporation|Oracle]], [[Salesforce.com|Salesforce]], and [[IBM]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Jack |last=Marshall |title=Google Launches New Data Tools for Marketers |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-launches-new-data-tools-for-marketers-1458043217 |publisher=''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' |date=March 15, 2016 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>

==== Business incubator ====
On September 24, 2012,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2012/09/celebrating-spirit-of-entrepreneurship.html|title=Celebrating the spirit of entrepreneurship with the new Google for Entrepreneurs|website=Official Google Blog|language=en|access-date=March 20, 2018}}</ref> Google launched [[Google for Entrepreneurs]], a largely not-for-profit [[business incubator]] providing startups with [[Coworking|co-working spaces]] known as Campuses, with assistance to startup founders that may include workshops, conferences, and mentorships.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/224522|title=How Google Wants to Make Starting Up Easier for Entrepreneurs|last=Fell|first=Jason|date=September 27, 2012|work=Entrepreneur|access-date=March 20, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Presently, there are 7 Campus locations in [[Berlin]], [[London]], [[Madrid]], [[Seoul]], [[São Paulo]], [[Tel Aviv]], and [[Warsaw]].

=== Consumer services ===

==== Web-based services ====
Google offers [[Gmail]], and the newer variant [[Inbox by Gmail|Inbox]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Darrell |last=Etherington |title=Google's Inbox is A New Email App From The Gmail Team Designed Not To Be Gmail |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/10/22/google-inbox/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=October 22, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> for [[email]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Gayomali |title=When Gmail Launched On April 1, 2004, People Thought It Was A Joke |url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3028513/when-gmail-launched-on-april-1-2004-people-thought-it-was-a-joke |website=[[Fast Company (magazine)|Fast Company]] |publisher=Mansueto Ventures |date=April 1, 2014 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Google Calendar]] for time-management and scheduling,<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google Calendar update makes it easier to track your New Year's fitness goals |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/1/5/14175830/google-calendar-track-fitness-goals-health-data |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=January 5, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Google Maps]] for mapping, navigation and [[satellite imagery]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Mitchel |last=Broussard |title=Google Maps Introduces New Location Sharing Feature With Real-Time Friend Tracking |url=https://www.macrumors.com/2017/03/22/google-maps-location-sharing/ |website=[[MacRumors]] |date=March 22, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Google Drive]] for [[File hosting service|cloud storage]] of files,<ref name="verge-drive-announced">{{cite web |first=T.C. |last=Sottek |title=Google Drive officially launches with 5GB free storage, Google Docs integration |url=https://www.theverge.com/2012/4/24/2971025/google-drive-official-launch-features |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=April 24, 2012 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Google Docs]], [[Google Sheets|Sheets]] and [[Google Slides|Slides]] for productivity,<ref name="verge-drive-announced" /> [[Google Photos]] for photo storage and sharing,<ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Google Photos Breaks Free Of Google+, Now Offers Free, Unlimited Storage |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/05/28/google-photos-breaks-free-of-google-now-offers-free-unlimited-storage/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=May 28, 2015 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Google Keep]] for [[note-taking]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dan |last=Graziano |title=Google launches Google Keep note-taking service [video] |url=http://bgr.com/2013/03/20/google-keep-annnounced-388095/ |website=[[Boy Genius Report|BGR]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]] |date=March 20, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> [[Google Translate]] for language translation,<ref>{{cite web |first=Lisa |last=Eadicicco |title=Google's Translation App Is About To Get Much Better |url=http://time.com/4572942/google-translate-app-update-2016/ |website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=November 16, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> [[YouTube]] for video viewing and sharing,<ref>{{cite web |first=Saba |last=Hamedy |title=People now spend 1 billion hours watching YouTube every day |url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/27/youtube-one-billion-hours-of-video-daily/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=February 28, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> and [[Google+]], [[Google Allo|Allo]], and [[Google Duo|Duo]] for social interaction.<ref>{{cite web |first=Steven |last=Levy |title=Inside Google+ - How the search giant plans to go social |url=https://www.wired.com/2011/06/inside-google-plus-social/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Condé Nast]] |date=June 28, 2011 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ingrid |last=Lunden |title=Google debuts Allo, an AI-based chat app using its new assistant bot, smart replies and more |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/05/18/google-allo-chat-app/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=May 18, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=Google Duo makes mobile video calls fast and simple |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/5/18/11690728/google-duo-video-call-app-vs-apple-facetime-io-2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=May 18, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref>

In April 2018, Google introduced the curated job feature for Indian users to search jobs more efficiently. The feature is built in coordination with major job search platforms like Aasaanjobs, Freshersworld, Headhonchos, IBM Talent Management Solutions, LinkedIn and many more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://india.googleblog.com/2018/04/making-it-easier-to-search-for-jobs-in.html|title=Making it easier to search for jobs in India|date=24 April 2018|website=Google India Blog}}</ref>

In May 2018, Google launched a new app named Neighbourly in India through which users can explore information about local places and also know about the people living nearby.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inc42.com/buzz/google-launches-new-app-neighbourly-in-india/|title=Here Comes Google’s New Friendly Neighbourhood App — ‘Neighbourly’|date=31 May 2018|website=Inc42 Media}}</ref>

In August 2018, Google introduced Navlekha (a Sanskrit word meaning, “a new way to write.”) initiative, which will help Indian authors to publish their content in regional languages.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inc42.com/buzz/googles-navlekha-to-help-indians-publish-content-in-regional-language/|title=Google’s Navlekha To Help Indians Publish Content in Regional Language|date=28 August 2018|website=Inc42 Media}}</ref>

On 7 September 2018, Google launched a mobile app for Android named ‘Blog Compass’ to help bloggers track the visitors and explore through the most relevant and trending topics to write.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://inc42.com/buzz/google-launches-blog-compass-for-online-bloggers/|title=Google Launches Blog Compass For Online Bloggers|date=8 September 2018|website=Inc42 Media}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://india.googleblog.com/2018/09/introducing-blog-compass-by-google.html|title=Introducing Blog Compass by Google|date=7 September 2018|website=Google India Blog}}</ref>

==== Software ====
Google develops the [[Android (operating system)|Android]] [[mobile operating system]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Erick |last=Schonfeld |title=Breaking: Google Announces Android and Open Handset Alliance |url=https://techcrunch.com/2007/11/05/breaking-google-announces-android-and-open-handset-alliance/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=November 5, 2007 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> as well as its [[Android Wear|smartwatch]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Dante |last=D'Orazio |title=Google reveals Android Wear, an operating system for smartwatches |url=https://www.theverge.com/2014/3/18/5522226/google-reveals-android-wear-an-operating-system-designed-for |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 18, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> [[Android TV|television]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Josh |last=Ong |title=Google announces Android TV to bring 'voice input, user experience and content' to the living room |url=https://thenextweb.com/google/2014/06/25/android-tv-google-io-2014/ |website=The Next Web |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> [[Android Auto|car]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Alex |last=Wilhelm |title=Google Announces Android Auto, Promises Enabled Cars By The End Of 2014 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2014/06/25/google-announces-android-auto-promises-enabled-cars-by-end-of-2014/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 25, 2014 |accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref> and [[Internet of things]]-enabled [[Android Things|smart devices]] variations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jacob |last=Kastrenakes |title=Android Things is Google's new OS for smart devices |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/12/13/13924996/android-things-announced-smart-home-iot-operating-system |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=December 13, 2016 |accessdate=April 4, 2017}}</ref>

It also develops the [[Google Chrome]] web browser,<ref>{{cite web |first1=Sundar |last1=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=A fresh take on the browser |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2008/09/fresh-take-on-browser.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=September 1, 2008 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref> and [[Chrome OS]], an operating system based on Chrome.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Sundar |last1=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=Introducing the Google Chrome OS |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2009/07/introducing-google-chrome-os.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=July 7, 2009 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref>

==== Hardware ====
In January 2010, Google released [[Nexus One]], the first Android phone under its own, "Nexus", brand.<ref>{{cite web |first=MG |last=Siegler |title=The Droid You're Looking For: Live From The Nexus One Event |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/01/05/nexus-one-event/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=January 5, 2010 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref> It spawned a number of phones and tablets under the "Nexus" branding<ref>{{cite web |first=Florence |last=Ion |title=From Nexus One to Nexus 10: a brief history of Google's flagship devices |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2013/05/from-the-nexus-one-to-the-nexus-10-a-brief-history-of-nexus-devices/ |website=[[Ars Technica]] |publisher=[[Condé Nast]] |date=May 15, 2013 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> until its eventual discontinuation in 2016, replaced by a new brand called, [[Pixel (smartphone)|Pixel]].<ref name="Pixel inside story">{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=The Google Phone: The inside story of Google's bold bet on hardware |url=https://www.theverge.com/a/google-pixel-phone-new-hardware-interview-2016 |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref>

In 2011, the [[Chromebook]] was introduced, described as a "new kind of computer" running [[Chrome OS]].<ref>{{cite web |first1=Sundar |last1=Pichai |first2=Linus |last2=Upson |title=A new kind of computer: Chromebook |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2011/05/new-kind-of-computer-chromebook.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=May 11, 2011 |accessdate=November 22, 2016}}</ref>

In July 2013, Google introduced the [[Chromecast]] dongle, that allows users to stream content from their smartphones to televisions.<ref>{{cite web |first=Adi |last=Robertson |title=Google reveals Chromecast: video streaming to your TV from any device for $35 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2013/7/24/4552204/google-reveals-chromecast-tv-streaming |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=July 24, 2013 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google Chromecast takes on streaming content to TV |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-23514400 |website=[[BBC News]] |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=July 31, 2013 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>

In June 2014, Google announced [[Google Cardboard]], a simple cardboard viewer that lets user place their smartphone in a special front compartment to view [[virtual reality]] (VR) media.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=O'Toole |title=Google's cardboard virtual-reality goggles |url=http://money.cnn.com/2014/06/25/technology/innovation/google-cardboard/ |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=June 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Erik |last=Kain |title=Google Cardboard Is Google's Awesomely Weird Answer To Virtual Reality |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/erikkain/2014/06/26/google-cardboard-is-googles-awesomely-weird-answer-to-virtual-reality/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=June 26, 2014 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>

In April 2016, ''[[Recode]]'' reported that Google had hired Rick Osterloh, [[Motorola Mobility]]'s former President, to head Google's new hardware division.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Mark |last1=Bergen |first2=Ina |last2=Fried |title=Google is building a new hardware division under former Motorola chief Rick Osterloh |url=http://www.recode.net/2016/4/28/11586518/google-hardware-division-rick-osterloh |website=[[Recode]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=April 28, 2016 |accessdate=October 9, 2016}}</ref> In October 2016, Osterloh stated that "a lot of the innovation that we want to do now ends up requiring controlling the end-to-end user experience",<ref name="Pixel inside story" /> and Google announced several hardware platforms:
* The [[Pixel (smartphone)|Pixel and Pixel XL]] smartphones with the [[Google Assistant]], a next-generation contextual voice assistant, built-in.<ref>{{cite web |first=Vlad |last=Savov |title=Pixel 'phone by Google' announced |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161028/google-phone-announced-pixel-xl-price-release-date-specs |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref>
* [[Google Home]], an [[Amazon Echo]]-like voice assistant placed in the house that can answer voice queries, play music, find information from apps (calendar, weather etc.), and control third-party smart home appliances (users can tell it to turn on the lights, for example).<ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=Google Home is smart, loud, and kind of cute |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13156676/google-home-assistant-speaker-photos-video-device-hands-on |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref>
* [[Google Daydream|Daydream View]] [[virtual reality]] headset that lets [[Android (operating system)|Android]] users with compatible Daydream-ready smartphones put their phones in the headset and enjoy VR content.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Adi |last1=Robertson |first2=Jacob |last2=Kastrenakes |title=Google's Daydream View VR headset goes on sale next month for $79 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13161506/google-vr-headset-photos-daydream-view-virtual-reality |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref>
* [[Google Wifi]], a connected set of [[Wi-Fi]] routers to simplify and extend coverage of home Wi-Fi.<ref>{{cite web |first=Dieter |last=Bohn |title=The Google Wifi routers are little white pucks you can scatter throughout your house |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/10/4/13157680/google-wifi-router-photos-hands-on |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=October 4, 2016 |accessdate=October 8, 2016}}</ref>

=== Internet services ===
In February 2010, Google announced the [[Google Fiber]] project, with experimental plans to build an ultra-high-speed broadband network for 50,000 to 500,000 customers in one or more American cities.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Minnie |last1=Ingersoll |first2=James |last2=Kelly |title=Think big with a gig: Our experimental fiber network |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2010/02/think-big-with-gig-our-experimental.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Erick |last=Schonfeld |title=Google Plans To Deliver 1Gb/sec Fiber-Optic Broadband Network To More Than 50,000 Homes |url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/02/10/google-fiber-optic-network-home/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=February 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref> Following Google's corporate restructure to make [[Alphabet Inc.]] its parent company, Google Fiber was moved to Alphabet's Access division.<ref>{{cite web |first=Kevin |last=McLaughlin |title=Inside the Battle Over Google Fiber |url=https://www.theinformation.com/articles/inside-the-battle-over-google-fiber |website=The Information |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Statt |title=Alphabet is putting serious pressure on Google Fiber to cut costs |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/8/25/12652734/google-fiber-access-alphabet-layoffs-wireless-internet |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=August 25, 2016 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>

In April 2015, Google announced [[Project Fi]], a mobile virtual network operator, that combines Wi-Fi and cellular networks from different telecommunication providers in an effort to enable seamless connectivity and fast Internet signal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Nick |last=Fox |title=Say hi to Fi: A new way to say hello |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.no/2015/04/project-fi.html |website=Official Google Blog |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=David |last=Goldman |title=Google launches 'Project Fi' wireless service |url=http://money.cnn.com/2015/04/22/technology/google-project-fi-wireless-service/ |website=[[CNN]] |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ellen |last=Huet |title=Google Unveils Its 'Project Fi' Wireless Service |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ellenhuet/2015/04/22/google-unveils-wireless-service-project-fi/ |website=[[Forbes]] |date=April 22, 2015 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>

In September 2016, Google began its Google Station initiative, a project for public Wi-Fi at railway stations in India. Caesar Sengupta, VP for Google's next billion users, told ''[[The Verge]]'' that 15,000 people get online for the first time thanks to Google Station and that 3.5 million people use the service every month. The expansion meant that Google was looking for partners around the world to further develop the initiative, which promised "high-quality, secure, easily accessible Wi-Fi".<ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Byford |title=Google Station is a new platform that aims to make public Wi-Fi better |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/9/27/13070922/google-station-public-wi-fi-india |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=September 27, 2016 |accessdate=October 23, 2016}}</ref> By December, Google Station had been deployed at 100 railway stations,<ref>{{cite web |first=Brian |last=Heater |title=After arriving at 100th railway station in India, Google's WiFi is set to hit another 100 in 2017 |url=https://techcrunch.com/2016/12/29/google-india-wifi/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=December 29, 2016 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref> and in February, Google announced its intention to expand beyond railway stations, with a plan to bring citywide Wi-Fi to [[Pune]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Stephen |last=Hall |title=Google Station expands beyond rail stations to bring citywide WiFi to Pune, India |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/02/09/google-station-expands-beyond-rail-stations-to-bring-citywide-wifi-to-pune-india/ |website=9to5Google |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Manish |last=Singh |title=Indian city to become the first in the world to get Google Station public Wi-Fi network |url=http://mashable.com/2017/02/09/google-station-pune-india/ |website=[[Mashable]] |date=February 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 12, 2017}}</ref>

{{as of|2018|October|}}, [[Orange S.A.|Orange]] has teamed up with Google in order to create a [[Transatlantic communications cable|transatlantic]] undersea cable to share data between the United States and France at faster speeds. Planned to begin operation in 2020, the cable is purported to transfer information at rates “more than 30 terabits per second, per [fibre] pair”. The cable will span approximately 6600 [[kilometers]] in length.<ref>{{cite web|title=Google and Orange building cable between US and France |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/oct/15/google-orange-building-cable-between-us-france}}</ref>

=== Other products ===
Google launched its [[Google News]] service in 2002, an automated service which summarizes news articles from various websites.<ref>{{Cite news |first=Joshua |last=Macht |title=Automatic for the People |url=http://www.time.com/time/business/article/0,8599,356152,00.html |work=Time |date=September 30, 2002}}</ref> In March 2005, [[Agence France Presse]] (AFP) sued Google for copyright infringement in federal court in the District of Columbia, a case which Google settled for an undisclosed amount in a pact that included a license of the full text of AFP articles for use on Google News.<ref>{{Cite journal |first=Hannibal |last=Travis |title=Opting Out of the Internet in the United States and the European Union: Copyright, Safe Harbors, and International Law |ssrn=1221642 |journal=Notre Dame Law Review |volume=55 |pages=391–92 |year=2008}}</ref>

In May 2011, Google announced [[Google Wallet]], a mobile application for wireless payments.<ref>{{cite news |first=Tara |last=Bernard |title=Google Unveils App for Paying With Phone |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/27/technology/27google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 26, 2011 |accessdate=November 29, 2016}}</ref>

In 2013, Google launched [[Google Shopping Express]], a delivery service initially available only in San Francisco and Silicon Valley.<ref>{{cite news |last=Somerville |first=Heather |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/business/ci_24171776/exclusive-google-same-day-delivery-makes-public-debut |title=Google same-day delivery makes public debut |newspaper=Mercury News |date=September 25, 2013}}</ref>

[[Google Alerts]] is a content [[change detection and notification]] service, offered by the [[search engine]] company Google. The service sends emails to the user when it finds new results—such as web pages, newspaper articles, or blogs—that match the user's search term.<ref>{{cite web |title=What are Google Alerts? |url=https://support.google.com/alerts/answer/175925 |accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://theundercoverrecruiter.com/how-use-google-alerts-live-job-search/ |title=How to Use Google Alerts for a Live Job Search |publisher=The Under Cover Recruiter}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/quickerbettertech/2014/11/03/this-little-service-absolutely-crushes-google-alerts/ |title=This Little Service Absolutely Crushes Google Alerts |publisher=[[Forbes]]}}</ref>

In July 2015 Google released [[DeepDream]], an image recognition software capable of creating psychedelic images using a [[convolutional neural network]].<ref name="codexample">{{cite web |first1=Alexander |last1=Mordvintsev |first2=Christopher |last2=Olah |first3=Mike |last3=Tyka |year=2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708233542/http://googleresearch.blogspot.co.uk/2015/07/deepdream-code-example-for-visualizing.html |archivedate=July 8, 2015 |url=http://googleresearch.blogspot.co.uk/2015/07/deepdream-code-example-for-visualizing.html |title=DeepDream&nbsp;— a code example for visualizing Neural Networks |publisher=Google Research}}</ref><ref name="goingdeeper">{{cite web |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703064823/http://googleresearch.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/inceptionism-going-deeper-into-neural.html |archivedate=July 3, 2015 |url=http://googleresearch.blogspot.co.uk/2015/06/inceptionism-going-deeper-into-neural.html |title=Inceptionism: Going Deeper into Neural Networks |publisher=Google Research |first1=Alexander |last1=Mordvintsev |first2=Christopher |last2=Olah |first3=Mike |last3=Tyka |year=2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/google/11712495/Google-unleashes-machine-dreaming-software-on-the-public-nightmarish-images-flood-the-internet.html |title=Google unleashes machine dreaming software on the public, nightmarish images flood the internet |date=July 2, 2015 |accessdate=July 25, 2015 |work=The Telegraph |author=James Titcomb}}</ref>

Google introduced its Family Link service in March 2017, letting parents buy [[Android Nougat]]-based Android devices for kids under 13 years of age and create a Google account through the app, with the parents controlling the apps installed, monitor the time spent using the device, and setting a "Bedtime" feature that remotely locks the device.<ref>{{cite web |first=Pavni |last=Diwanji |title=Introducing the Family Link app: Helping families navigate technology together |url=https://blog.google/topics/families/introducing-family-link-app-helping-families-navigate-technology-together/ |website=The Keyword Google Blog |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ashley |last=Carman |title=Google built a new app so your kids can have a Google account, too |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/3/15/14936424/google-family-link-app-release-parental-controls |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sarah |last=Perez |title=Google introduces Family Link, its own parental control software for Android |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/15/google-introduces-family-link-its-own-parental-control-software-for-android/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 16, 2017}}</ref>

In April 2017, Google launched AutoDraw, a web-based tool using [[artificial intelligence]] and [[machine learning]] to recognize users' drawings and replace scribbles with related [[Stock photography|stock images]] that have been created by professional artists.<ref>{{cite web |first=Stefanie |last=Fogel |title=Google's AutoDraw turns your clumsy scribbles into art |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/04/11/google-autodraw/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=April 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Titcomb |title=Google's new drawing app can turn your terrible sketches into works of art |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2017/04/12/google-autodraw-can-turn-terrible-sketches-works-art/ |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |publisher=[[Telegraph Media Group]] |date=April 12, 2017 |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Claire |last=Reilly |title=Does Google's AutoDraw AI grasp modern art better than you? |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-autodraw-ai-does-it-understand-modern-art/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=April 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref> The tool is built using the same technology as QuickDraw, an experimental game from Google's Creative Lab where users were tasked with drawing objects that algorithms would recognize within 20 seconds.<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google's AutoDraw uses machine learning to help you draw like a pro |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/04/11/googles-autodraw-uses-machine-learning-to-help-you-draw-like-a-pro/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=April 11, 2017 |accessdate=April 12, 2017}}</ref>

In May 2017, Google added "Family Groups" to several of its services. The feature, which lets users create a group consisting of their family members' individual Google accounts, lets users add their "Family Group" as a collaborator to shared albums in [[Google Photos]], shared notes in [[Google Keep]], and common events in [[Google Calendar]]. At announcement, the feature is limited to Australia, Brazil, Canada, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Japan, Mexico, New Zealand, Russia, Spain, United Kingdom and United States.<ref>{{cite web |first=Chris |last=Welch |title=Google adds easy, simple family sharing to Calendar, Keep, and Photos |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/5/23/15681668/google-family-calendar-keep-photos-now-available |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=May 23, 2017 |accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Ryan |last=Whitwam |title=Google family groups make it easy to share photos, calendars, Keep, YouTube TV, and more |url=http://www.androidpolice.com/2017/05/23/google-family-groups-make-easy-share-photos-calendars-youtube-tv/ |website=Android Police |date=May 23, 2017 |accessdate=May 24, 2017}}</ref>

===APIs===
[[Google APIs]] are a set of [[application programming interface]]s (APIs) developed by Google which allow communication with [[Google Services]] and their integration to other services. Examples of these include Search, Gmail, Translate or Google Maps. Third-party apps can use these APIs to take advantage of or extend the functionality of the existing services.

===Other websites===
[[Google Developers]] is Google's site for [[software development]] tools, APIs, and technical resources. The site contains documentation on using Google developer tools and APIs—including discussion groups and blogs for developers using Google's developer products.

[[Google Labs]] was a page created by Google to demonstrate and test new projects.

Google owns the top-level domain '''1e100.net''' which is used for some servers within Google's network. The name is a reference to the scientific [[E notation]] representation for 1 googol, {{math|1E100 {{=}} 1 × 10<sup>100</sup>}}.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://support.google.com/faqs/answer/174717 |title=What is 1e100.net |website=Google Support |access-date=December 10, 2015}}</ref>

In March 2017, Google launched a new website, opensource.google.com, to publish its internal documentation for Google Open Source projects.<ref>{{cite web |first=Frederic |last=Lardinois |title=Google launches new site to showcase its open source projects and processes |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/03/28/google-launches-new-site-to-showcase-its-open-source-projects-and-processes/ |website=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=March 28, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Steven J. |last=Vaughan-Nichols |title=Google presents its open-source goodies to the world |url=http://www.zdnet.com/article/google-presents-its-open-source-goodies-to-the-world/ |website=[[ZDNet]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=March 29, 2017 |accessdate=March 29, 2017}}</ref>

In June 2017, Google launched "We Wear Culture", a searchable archive of 3,000 years of global fashion. The archive, a result of collaboration between Google and over 180 museums, schools, fashion institutes, and other organizations, also offers curated exhibits of specific fashion topics and their impact on society.<ref>{{cite web |first=Marc |last=Bain |title=Google has built a stunning, searchable archive of 3,000 years of world fashion |url=https://qz.com/1002651/google-has-built-a-stunning-searchable-archive-of-3000-years-of-world-fashion/ |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |date=June 11, 2017 |accessdate=June 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Maria |last=Ward |title=Anna Wintour, Andrew Bolton, and More Celebrate the Launch of We Wear Culture |url=http://www.vogue.com/article/google-we-wear-culture-metropolitan-museum-of-art-andrew-bolton-anna-wintour |website=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |publisher=[[Condé Nast]] |date=June 9, 2017 |accessdate=June 11, 2017}}</ref>

== Corporate affairs and culture ==
[[File:Eric Schmidt at the 37th G8 Summit in Deauville 037.jpg|thumb|upright|left|[[Eric Schmidt]]]]
[[File:Schmidt-Brin-Page-20080520.jpg|thumb|Then-CEO, now Chairman of Google [[Eric Schmidt]] with cofounders [[Sergey Brin]] and [[Larry Page]] (left to right) in 2008.|alt=Eric Schmidt, Sergey Brin, and Larry Page sitting together]]
[[File:20 colleges with the most alumni at Google.png|upright=1.35|frameless|right]]

On ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' magazine's list of the best companies to work for, Google ranked first in 2007, 2008 and 2012,<ref name="best_company">{{Cite journal |last1=Levering |first1=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |editor1-first=Andrew |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |date=January 22, 2007 |title=In good company |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=155 |issue=1 |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2007/01/22/8398125/index.htm |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Levering |first1=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |editor1-first=Andrew |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |date=February 4, 2008 |title=The 2008 list |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=157 |issue=2 |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2008/full_list/index.html |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |title=The 2012 list |journal=Fortune Magazine |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/best-companies/2012/full_list/ |accessdate=February 26, 2012}}</ref> and fourth in 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Levering |first1=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |editor1-first=Andrew |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |date=February 2, 2009 |title=The 2009 list |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=159 |issue=2 |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2009/full_list/index.html |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Levering |first1=Robert |last2=Moskowitz |first2=Milton |editor1-first=Andrew |editor1-last=Serwer |editor1-link=Andrew Serwer |date=February 8, 2010 |title=The 2010 list |journal=Fortune Magazine |volume=161 |issue=2 |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2010/full_list/ |accessdate=June 19, 2010}}</ref> Google was also nominated in 2010 to be the world's most attractive employer to graduating students in the Universum Communications talent attraction index.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.universumglobal.com/IDEAL-Employer-Rankings/Global-Top-50 |title=The World's Most Attractive Employers 2010 |date=September 28, 2010 |publisher=Universum Global |accessdate=October 28, 2010}}</ref> Google's corporate philosophy includes principles such as "you can make money without doing evil," "you can be serious without a suit," and "work should be challenging and the challenge should be fun."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/corporate/tenthings.html |title=Our Philosophy |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=June 20, 2010}}</ref>

=== Innovation Time Off policy ===
{{Anchor|Innovation Time Off}}
As a motivation technique, Google uses a policy known as Innovation Time Off, where Google engineers are encouraged to spend 20% of their work time on projects that interest them. Some of Google's services, such as Gmail, Google News, [[Orkut]], and AdSense originated from these independent endeavors.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Bharat |last1=Mediratta |first2=Julie |last2=Bick |title=The Google Way: Give Engineers Room |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/21/jobs/21pre.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 21, 2007 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> In a talk at Stanford University, [[Marissa Mayer]], Google's Vice-President of Search Products and User Experience until July 2012, showed that half of all new product launches in the second half of 2005 had originated from the Innovation Time Off.<ref>{{Cite video |people=Mayer, Marissa (speaker) |date=June 30, 2006 |title=Marissa Mayer at Stanford University |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=soYKFWqVVzg |medium=Seminar |publisher=Martin Lafrance |accessdate=June 20, 2010 |time=11:33 |quote=Fifty percent of what Google launched in the second half of 2005 actually got built out of 20% time.}}</ref>

=== ''The New York Times'' ''exposé'' (2018) ===

On 25 October 2018, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published the ''[[Investigative journalism|exposé]]'', "How Google Protected [[Andy Rubin]], the ‘Father of Android’". The company subsequently announced that "48 employees have been fired over the last two years" for sexual misconduct.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Welch |first1=Chris |title=Google says 48 people have been fired for sexual harassment in the last two years |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/25/18024486/google-sexual-harassment-people-fired-rubin-2-years-ceo |accessdate=31 October 2018 |publisher=The Verge |date=25 October 2018}}</ref> A week after the article appeared, [[Google X]] (renamed X Development LLC in 2015) executive Rich DeVaul resigned pursuant to  a complaint of [[sexual harassment]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Musil |first1=Steven |title=Google exec accused of sexual harassment leaves company |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-exec-accused-of-sexual-harassment-leaves-company/ |accessdate=31 October 2018 |publisher=CNET |date=30 October 2018}}</ref>

=== Employees ===
[[File:Noogler.png|thumb|upright|alt=Asian man in his twenties wearing a blue, green, yellow, and red propeller hat that says "Noogle"|New employees are called "Nooglers," and are given a [[Beanie (North America)#Propeller beanie|propeller beanie cap]] to wear on their first Friday.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.zorgloob.com/2004/09/23/noogler-chez-google/ |title=Noogler chez Google |language=French}}</ref>]]
{{As of|2018|3|31|alt=As of March 2018,}} Google has 85,050 employees.<ref name="EmployeesAsOf2018Q1" /> Google's {{as of|2017|6|29|alt=2017}} diversity report states that 31 percent of its workforce are women and 69 percent are men, with the ethnicity of its workforce being predominantly white (56%) and Asian (35%).<ref name="2017DiversityReport">{{cite blog|url=https://www.blog.google/topics/diversity/making-progress-diversity-and-inclusion/|title=Making progress on diversity and inclusion|last=Naughton|first=Eileen|date=June 29, 2017|department=Diversity|website=The Keyword|publisher=Google|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517170958/https://www.blog.google/topics/diversity/making-progress-diversity-and-inclusion/|archive-date=May 17, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=May 17, 2018}}{{pb}}{{cite news|last=Yurieff|first=Kaya|date=June 29, 2017|title=Google struggles to increase workforce diversity|url=https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/29/technology/google-diversity-report/index.html|dead-url=no|department=CNNTech|work=[[CNNMoney]]|publisher=[[Time Warner]]|location=New York|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517174524/https://money.cnn.com/2017/06/29/technology/google-diversity-report/index.html|archive-date=May 17, 2018|access-date=May 17, 2018}}</ref> Within tech roles, however, 20 percent were women; and 25 percent of leadership roles were held by women.<ref name="2017DiversityReport" /> The report also announced that [[Intel]]'s former vice-president, [[Chief diversity officer|CDO]], and [[Chief human resources officer|CHRO]] Danielle Brown would be joining Google as its new Vice-President of Diversity.<ref name="2017DiversityReport" /> {{update inline span|text=A March 2013 report was presented at EclipseCon2013 which detailed that Google had over 10,000 developers based in more than 40 offices.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.eclipsecon.org/2013/sites/eclipsecon.org.2013/files/2013-03-24%20Continuous%20Integration%20at%20Google%20Scale.pdf|title=Continuous Integration at Google Scale|last=Micco|first=John|date=March 24, 2013|website=EclipseCon|publisher=[[Eclipse Foundation]]|page=2|format=PDF|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180517181532/https://www.eclipsecon.org/2013/sites/eclipsecon.org.2013/files/2013-03-24%20Continuous%20Integration%20at%20Google%20Scale.pdf|archive-date=May 17, 2018|dead-url=no|access-date=May 17, 2018|quote=Speed and Scale[:] >10,000 developers in 40+ offices}}</ref>|date=May 2018|reason=This information is over five years old and the growth of Google since then suggests that the number might have doubled or tripled since then. Google's Form 10-Q SEC filing for Q1 of 2018 does not appear to break down employee numbers.}}

Google's employees are hired based on a hierarchical system. Employees are split into six hierarchies based on experience and can range "from entry-level data center workers at level one to managers and experienced engineers at level six."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/09/08/google-gender-pay-gap-spreadsheet-finds-men-paid-more-than-women.html|title=Google workers collected data showing their male colleagues make more than women|last=Wakabayashi|first=Daisuke|date=September 8, 2017|work=CNBC|access-date=September 25, 2017}}</ref>

Following the company's IPO in 2004, founders Sergey Brin and Larry Page and CEO Eric Schmidt requested that their [[One-dollar salary|base salary be cut to $1]]. Subsequent offers by the company to increase their salaries were turned down, primarily because their main compensation continues to come from owning stock in Google. Before 2004, Schmidt made $250,000 per year, and Page and Brin each received an annual salary of $150,000.<ref>{{cite web |first=Paul R. |last=La Monica |title=Google leaders stick with $1 salary |url=http://money.cnn.com/2006/03/31/technology/google/index.htm |website=CNN Money |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=March 31, 2006 |accessdate=April 25, 2017}}</ref>

In March 2008, [[Sheryl Sandberg]], then vice-president of global online sales and operations, began her position as chief operating officer of Facebook.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/03/04/AR2008030402766.html |title=Facebook Raids Google for Executive |work=The Washington Post |date=March 5, 2008 |accessdate=March 31, 2008 |first=Michael |last=Liedtke}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://venturebeat.com/2008/03/04/facebook-hires-sheryl-sandberg-to-be-its-new-coo/ |title=Another Googler goes to Facebook: Sheryl Sandberg becomes new COO |publisher=Venture Beat |date=March 4, 2008 |accessdate=March 31, 2008}}</ref>
In 2009, early employee [[Tim Armstrong (executive)|Tim Armstrong]] left to become CEO of [[AOL]]. In July 2012, Google's first female engineer, [[Marissa Mayer]], left Google to become [[Yahoo!]]'s CEO.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rushie |first=Dominic |title=Google executive Marissa Mayer to become Yahoo CEO in surprise move |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2012/jul/16/google-marissa-mayer-yahoo-ceo |accessdate=September 1, 2012 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=July 16, 2012 |location=London}}</ref>

In January 2017, Google employees donated over $2 million to a crisis fund in support of [[refugees]]; the company matched the donation with an additional $2 million. Employees then organized a global workplace [[walk-out]], aided by the [[hashtag]] #GooglersUnite, to protest U.S. President [[Donald Trump]]'s [[Executive Order 13769|Muslim travel ban]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Newton |first1=Casey |title=Google employees staged a protest over Trump’s immigration ban |url=https://www.theverge.com/google/2017/1/30/14446466/google-immigration-protest-walkout-trump-googlers-unite |accessdate=7 November 2018 |agency=VOX Media Inc. |publisher=''The Verge'' |date=30 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Elias |first1=Jennifer |title=Google employees walk out in protest of Trump travel ban |url=https://www.bizjournals.com/sanjose/news/2017/01/30/google-employees-walk-out-in-protest-of-trump.html |accessdate=7 November 2018 |agency=American City Business Journals |publisher=''Silicon Valley Business Journal'' |date=30 January 2017}}</ref>

In late 2017, former [[Intel]] executive [[Diane Bryant]] became Chief Operating Officer of [[Google Cloud Platform|Google Cloud]].<ref>{{Cite web| last = Miller| first = Ron| title = Google Cloud brings in former Intel exec Diane Bryant as COO| website = TechCrunch| accessdate = December 31, 2017| url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/30/google-cloud-brings-in-former-intel-exec-diane-bryant-as-coo/}}</ref>

On 1 November 2018, Google employees staged a global walk-out to protest the company's handling of sexual harassment complaints, including the [[golden parachute]] exit of former executive [[Andy Rubin]];<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/google-walkout-live-pictures-of-protesting-google-workers-2018-11 |last1=Hamilton, et al |first1=Isobel Asher |title=PHOTOS: Google employees all over the world left their desk and walked out in protest over sexual misconduct |accessdate=6 November 2018 |publisher=''Business Insider'' |date=1 November 2018}}</ref> more than 20,000 employees and contractors participated.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Segarra |first1=Lisa Marie |title=More Than 20,000 Google Employees Participated in Walkout Over Sexual Harassment Policy |url=http://fortune.com/2018/11/03/google-employees-walkout-demands/ |accessdate=6 November 2018 |publisher=Fortune |date=3 November 2018}}</ref> CEO [[Sundar Pichai]] was reported to be in support of the protests.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Liedtke |first1=Michael |title=Google workers walk out to protest sexual misconduct |url=https://www.ohio.com/news/20181101/google-workers-walk-out-to-protest-sexual-misconduct |accessdate=6 November 2018 |agency=The Associated Press |publisher=Akron Beacon/Journal |date=1 November 2018 |location=San Francisco, Calf.}}</ref>

=== Office locations and headquarters ===
[[File:Google Mountain View campus garden.jpg|thumb|right|[[Google Mountain View]] campus garden]]

[[File:Google bike.jpg|thumb|left|Bicycles painted in the corporate color scheme are available for free use by any employee traveling around the Googleplex]]

==== Mountain View ====
{{Main|Googleplex}}

Google's headquarters in [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], California is referred to as "the [[Googleplex]]", a play on words on the number [[googolplex]] and the headquarters itself being a ''complex'' of buildings. The lobby is decorated with a piano, [[lava lamp]]s, old server clusters, and a projection of search queries on the wall. The hallways are full of exercise balls and bicycles. Many employees have access to the corporate recreation center. Recreational amenities are scattered throughout the campus and include a workout room with weights and rowing machines, locker rooms, washers and dryers, a massage room, assorted video games, [[table football]], a baby grand piano, a billiard table, and ping pong. In addition to the recreation room, there are snack rooms stocked with various foods and drinks, with special emphasis placed on nutrition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/corporate/culture.html |title=About the Googleplex |accessdate=March 5, 2008}}</ref> Free food is available to employees 24/7, with the offerings provided by paid vending machines [[Pro rata|prorated]] based on and favoring those of better nutritional value.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/life/print/2011/07/what-googles-famous-cafeterias-can-teach-us-about-health/241876/ |title=What Google's Famous Cafeterias Can Teach Us About Health |publisher=[[The Atlantic]] |author=[[Marion Nestle]] |date=July 2011 |accessdate=May 8, 2013}}</ref>

Google's extensive amenities are not available to all of its workers. Temporary workers such as book scanners do not have access to shuttles, Google cafes, or other perks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://searchengineland.com/does-google-have-a-class-system-for-googlers-75457 |title=Does Google Have A Class System For Googlers? |publisher=[[SearchEngineLand]] |author=[[Barry Schwartz (technologist)|Barry Schwartz]] |date=May 2, 2011 |accessdate=April 22, 2013}}</ref>

==== New York City ====
[[File:PONYA Inland Term 1 jeh.JPG|thumb|Google's New York City office building houses its largest advertising sales team.]]
In 2006, Google moved into about {{convert|300000|sqft|m2|-2}} of office space in New York City, at [[111 Eighth Avenue]] in Manhattan. The office was designed and built specially for Google, and houses its largest advertising sales team, which has been instrumental in securing large partnerships.<ref>{{cite web |first=Marguerite |last=Reardon |title=Google takes a bigger bite of Big Apple |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-takes-a-bigger-bite-of-big-apple/ |website=[[CNET]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |date=October 11, 2006 |accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref> The New York headquarters includes a game room, micro-kitchens, and a video game area.<ref>{{cite web |first=Annie Georgia |last=Greenberg |title=The Ultimate Office: Inside Google's NYC Compound |url=http://www.refinery29.com/google-office |website=[[Refinery29]] |date=September 11, 2012 |accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref> In 2010, Google bought the building housing the headquarter, in a deal that valued the property at around $1.9 billion, the biggest for a single building in the United States that year.<ref>{{cite web |first=Peter |last=Grant |title=Google to Buy New York Office Building |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748704377004575651380545769418 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]] |date=December 3, 2010 |accessdate=June 13, 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Sam |last=Gustin |title=Google buys giant New York building for $1.9 billion |url=https://www.wired.com/2010/12/google-nyc/ |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher=[[Condé Nast]] |date=December 22, 2010 |accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref> In February 2012, Google moved additional employees to the New York City campus, with a total of around 2,750 employees.<ref>{{cite web |first=Emily |last=Glazer |title=Google Web Grows in City |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204653604577251293275921060 |website=[[The Wall Street Journal]] |publisher=[[Dow Jones & Company]] |date=February 29, 2012 |accessdate=June 13, 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref> In 2018, Google's parent company Alphabet bought [[Chelsea Market]] building for $2.4 billion nearby its current New York HQ. The sale is touted as one of the most expensive real estate transactions for a single building in the history of New York.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://phys.org/news/2018-03-google-nyc-chelsea-bn.html|title=Google buys NYC's Chelsea Market building for $2.4 bn|access-date=June 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/03/20/google-bought-manhattans-chelsea-market-building-for-2-4-billion/|title=Google bought Manhattan's Chelsea Market building for $2.4 billion – TechCrunch|website=techcrunch.com|language=en-US|access-date=June 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-new-york-property-google-chelseamarke/google-closes-2-4-billion-chelsea-market-deal-to-expand-new-york-campus-idUSKBN1GW35U|title=Google closes $2.4 billion Chelsea Market deal to expand New York...|last=Editorial|first=Reuters|work=U.S.|access-date=June 1, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://uk.pcmag.com/news/93278/report-alphabet-is-buying-chelsea-market-for-over-2b|title=Report: Alphabet Is Buying Chelsea Market for Over $2B|date=February 9, 2018|work=PCMag UK|access-date=June 1, 2018|language=en-GB}}</ref>

==== Other U.S. cities ====
By late 2006, Google established a new headquarters for its AdWords division in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Mary Hayes |last=Weier |title=Inside Google's Michigan Office |url=http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/webdev/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=202600809 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080503233009/http://www.informationweek.com/news/internet/webdev/showArticle.jhtml?articleID=202600809 |website=[[InformationWeek]] |publisher=[[UBM plc]] |date=October 24, 2007 |archivedate=May 3, 2008 |accessdate=January 22, 2017 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> In November 2006, Google opened offices on [[Carnegie Mellon]]'s campus in [[Pittsburgh]], focusing on shopping-related advertisement coding and [[smartphone applications]] and programs.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/technology/10346550/detail.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hGpTE0LB?url=http://www.thepittsburghchannel.com/technology/10346550/detail.html |archivedate=June 4, 2009 |title=Google Completes Pittsburgh Office, Holds Open House |date=November 17, 2006 |accessdate=January 13, 2008 |publisher=[[WTAE TV|WTAE]] |deadurl=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/business/s_712700.html |title=Google search: Tech-minded workers |last=Olson |first=Thomas |date=December 8, 2010 |publisher=[[Trib Total Media]] |accessdate=December 8, 2010}}</ref> Other office locations in the U.S. include [[Atlanta, Georgia]]; [[Austin, Texas]]; [[Boulder, Colorado]]; [[Cambridge, Massachusetts]]; [[San Francisco]], [[California]]; [[Seattle, Washington]]; [[Kirkland, Washington]]; [[Birmingham, Michigan]]; [[Reston, Virginia]], and [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/about/company/facts/locations/ |title=Google locations }}</ref>

In October 2006, the company announced plans to install thousands of [[solar panel]]s to provide up to 1.6&nbsp;mega[[watt]]s of electricity, enough to satisfy approximately 30% of the campus' energy needs.<ref name="solar">{{cite web |last=Richmond |first=Riva |url=http://www.post1.net/lowem/entry/google_plans_to_build_huge |title=Google plans to build huge solar energy system for headquarters |website=post1.net |publisher=[[MarketWatch]] |date=October 17, 2006 |accessdate=October 17, 2006 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160519010259/http://www.post1.net/lowem/entry/google_plans_to_build_huge |archivedate=May 19, 2016 }}</ref> The system will be the largest [[Rooftop photovoltaic power station|solar power system]] constructed on a U.S. corporate campus and one of the largest on any corporate site in the world.<ref name="solar" /> In addition, Google announced in 2009 that it was deploying herds of [[goats]] to keep grassland around the Googleplex short, helping to prevent the threat from seasonal bush fires while also reducing the [[carbon footprint]] of mowing the extensive grounds.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2009/05/mowing-with-goats.html |title=Official Google Blog: Mowing with goats |date=May 1, 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/05/04/AR2009050400027.html |work=[[The Washington Post]] |title=My Day With The Google Goats |first=MG |last=Siegler |date=May 3, 2009 |accessdate=May 3, 2010}}</ref> The idea of trimming lawns using goats originated from [[Bob Widlar]], an engineer who worked for [[National Semiconductor]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.national.com/rap/Horrible/sheep.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/19990506135340/http://www.national.com/rap/Horrible/sheep.html |archivedate=May 6, 1999 |title=Sheep Mow Lawns |publisher=[[National Semiconductor]] |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> In 2008, Google faced accusations in ''[[Harper's Magazine]]'' of being an "energy glutton". The company was accused of employing its "[[Don't be evil]]" motto and its public [[energy-saving]] campaigns to cover up or make up for the massive amounts of energy its servers require.<ref>{{cite web |authorlink=Ginger Strand |last=Strand |first=Ginger |url=http://www.harpers.org/media/slideshow/annot/2008-03/index.html |title=Keyword: Evil |accessdate=April 9, 2008 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT7kP56x?url=http://www.harpers.org/media/slideshow/annot/2008-03/index.html |archivedate=June 12, 2009 }}</ref>

==== International locations ====
Internationally, Google has over 78 offices in more than 50 countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/intl/en/about/locations/?region=north-america|title=Google: Our Offices|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=April 19, 2018}}</ref> It also has product research and development operations in cities around the world, namely [[Sydney]] (birthplace location of [[Google Maps]])<ref>{{cite web |title=Sydney |url=https://careers.google.com/locations/sydney/ |website=Google Careers |accessdate=June 4, 2017}}</ref> and [[London]] (part of [[Android (operating system)|Android]] development).<ref>{{cite web |title=London |url=https://careers.google.com/locations/london/ |website=Google Careers |accessdate=June 4, 2017}}</ref>

In November 2013, Google announced plans for a new [[London]] headquarter, a notable 1 million square foot office able to accommodate 4,500 employees. Recognized as one of the biggest ever commercial property acquisitions at the time of the deal's announcement in January,<ref>{{cite web |first=Leo |last=Mirani |title=Inside Google's new 1-million-square-foot London office—three years before it's ready |url=https://qz.com/139794/inside-googles-new-1-million-square-foot-london-office-three-years-before-its-ready/ |website=[[Quartz (publication)|Quartz]] |publisher=[[Atlantic Media]] |date=November 1, 2013 |accessdate=March 15, 2017}}</ref> Google submitted plans for the new headquarter to the [[Camden London Borough Council|Camden Council]] in June 2017. The new building, if approved, will feature a rooftop garden with a running track, giant moving blinds, a swimming pool, and a multi-use games area for sports.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Vincent |title=Google's new London HQ is a 'landscraper' with a rooftop garden |url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/6/1/15723642/google-london-office-pictures-headquarters-kings-cross |website=[[The Verge]] |publisher=[[Vox Media]] |date=June 1, 2017 |accessdate=June 4, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Matt |last=Brian |title=Google's 'innovative' new London HQ features giant moving blinds |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/06/01/google-london-kings-cross-hq-plans-photos/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=June 1, 2017 |accessdate=June 4, 2017}}</ref>

In May 2015, Google announced its intention to create its own campus in [[Hyderabad]], India. The new campus, reported to be the company's largest outside the United States, will accommodate 13,000 employees.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google to build biggest campus outside US in Hyderabad |url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/google-to-build-biggest-campus-outside-us-in-hyderabad/ |website=[[The Indian Express]] |date=May 12, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Google's upcoming campus in Hyderabad to be its biggest outside the US |url=http://tech.firstpost.com/news-analysis/googles-upcoming-campus-in-hyderabad-to-be-its-biggest-outside-the-us-267059.html |website=[[Firstpost]] |publisher=[[Network 18]] |date=May 13, 2015 |accessdate=June 13, 2017}}</ref>

=== Doodles ===
{{Main|Google Doodle}}
{{As of|1998|since=y|post=,}} Google has been designing special, temporary alternate logos to place on their [[homepage]] intended to celebrate [[holiday]]s, events, achievements and people. The first Google [[Doodle]] was in honor of the [[Burning Man|Burning Man Festival]] of 1998.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodle4google/history.html |title=Doodle 4 Google |date= |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/doodles/burning-man-festival |title=Burning Man Festival |date=August 30, 1998 |accessdate=April 23, 2014}}</ref> The doodle was designed by [[Larry Page]] and [[Sergey Brin]] to notify users of their absence in case the servers crashed. Subsequent Google Doodles were designed by an outside contractor, until Larry and Sergey asked then-[[intern]] [[Dennis Hwang]] to design a logo for [[Bastille Day]] in 2000. From that point onward, Doodles have been organized and created by a team of employees termed "Doodlers".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/apr/12/meet-people-behind-google-doodles-logo |title=Meet the people behind the Google Doodles |publisher=The Guardian |date=April 12, 2014 |accessdate=September 27, 2014}}</ref>

=== Easter eggs and April Fools' Day jokes ===
{{Main|List of Google April Fools' Day jokes|List of Google Easter eggs}}

Google has a tradition of creating [[April Fools' Day]] jokes. On April 1, 2000, [[Google's hoaxes#2000|Google MentalPlex]] allegedly featured the use of mental power to search the web.<ref name="mentalplex">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/mentalplex/ |title=Google MentalPlex |date=April 1, 2000 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> In 2007, Google announced a free Internet service called [[TiSP]], or Toilet Internet Service Provider, where one obtained a connection by flushing one end of a [[optical fiber|fiber-optic]] cable down their toilet.<ref name="TiSP">{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/tisp/ |title=Welcome to Google TiSP |date=April 1, 2007 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 5, 2010}}</ref> Also in 2007, Google's Gmail page displayed an announcement for [[Gmail Paper]], allowing users to have email messages printed and shipped to them.<ref name="gmail_paper">{{cite web |url=http://mail.google.com/mail/help/paper/more.html |archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20080315144610/http://mail.google.com/mail/help/paper/more.html |dead-url=yes |archive-date=March 15, 2008 |title=Google Paper |date=April 1, 2000 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref>
In 2008, Google announced Gmail Custom time where users could change the time that the email was sent.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://mail.google.com/mail/help/customtime/index.html |title=Gmail Custom Time: Google makes custom time |date=April 14, 2011 |publisher=Google |accessdate=April 14, 2011}}</ref>

In 2010, Google changed its company name to Topeka in honor of [[Topeka, Kansas]], whose mayor changed the city's name to Google for a short amount of time in an attempt to sway Google's decision in its new [[Google Fiber|Google Fiber Project]].<ref name="Google Blog: A Different Kind of Company Name">{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/04/different-kind-of-company-name.html |title=A different kind of company name |last1=Schmidt |first1=Eric |date=April 1, 2010 |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2010/04/01/business/main6353136.shtml |title=April Fools: Google Changes Name to Topeka |date=April 1, 2010 |publisher=[[CBS News]] |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> In 2011, Google announced [[Gmail Motion]], an interactive way of controlling Gmail and the computer with body movements via the user's webcam.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.gmanews.tv/story/216708/technology/googles-gmail-motion-launched-april-1 |title=Google's GMail Motion launched April 1 |date=April 1, 2011 |publisher=[[GMA News]]}}</ref>

Google's services contain [[Easter egg (media)|easter eggs]], such as the [[Swedish Chef]]'s "Bork bork bork," [[Pig Latin]], "Hacker" or [[leet]]speak, [[Elmer Fudd]], [[International Talk Like a Pirate Day|Pirate]], and [[Klingon language|Klingon]] as language selections for its search engine.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/language_tools |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT77QDRS?url=http://www.google.com/language_tools |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |title=Language Tools |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 4, 2010 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> The search engine calculator provides the [[Answer to the Ultimate Question of Life, the Universe, and Everything]] from [[Douglas Adams]]' ''[[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/search?q=answer+to+life+the+universe+and+everything |title=Google Search Results for 'answer to life the universe and everything' |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref> When searching the word "recursion", the spell-checker's result for the properly spelled word is exactly the same word, creating a recursive link.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/search?q=recursion |title=Google Search Results for 'recursion' |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 4, 2010}}</ref>

When searching for the word "[[anagram]]," meaning a rearrangement of letters from one word to form other valid words, Google's suggestion feature displays "Did you mean: nag a ram?"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.google.com/search?q=anagram |title=anagram search |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=September 22, 2010}}</ref> In Google Maps, searching for directions between places separated by large bodies of water, such as Los Angeles and Tokyo, results in instructions to "[[kayak]] across the [[Pacific Ocean]]." During [[FIFA World Cup 2010]], search queries including "[[FIFA World Cup|World Cup]]" and "[[FIFA]]" caused the "Goooo...gle" page indicator at the bottom of every result page to read "Goooo...al!" instead.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://asia.cnet.com/crave/google-celebrates-world-cup-with-gooooooooooal-62111461.htm |title=Google celebrates World Cup with Gooooooooooal! |website=CNET Asia |date=June 9, 2010 |accessdate=May 18, 2011 |author=Chan, John}}</ref>

=== Philanthropy ===
{{Main|Google.org}}

In 2004, Google formed the not-for-profit philanthropic [[Google.org]], with a start-up fund of $1&nbsp;billion.<ref name="philanthropy">{{cite web |url=http://www.google.org/about.html |title=About the Foundation |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 16, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100714080922/http://www.google.org/about.html |archivedate=July 14, 2010}}</ref> The mission of the organization is to create awareness about [[climate change]], global public health, and global poverty. One of its first projects was to develop a viable [[plug-in hybrid]] [[electric vehicle]] that can attain 100 miles per gallon. Google hired [[Larry Brilliant]] as the program's executive director in 2004<ref>{{cite web |first=Katie |last=Hafner |title=Philanthropy Google's Way: Not the Usual |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/14/technology/14google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 14, 2006 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> and Megan Smith has {{as of|2009|2|23|alt=since}} replaced him has director.<ref>{{cite web |first=Miguel |last=Helft |title=Google Chief for Charity Steps Down on Revamp |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/24/technology/companies/24google.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=February 23, 2009 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

In 2008, Google announced its "project 10<sup>100</sup>" which accepted ideas for how to help the community and then allowed Google users to vote on their favorites.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.project10tothe100.com/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5hT8OddCZ?url=http://www.project10tothe100.com/ |archivedate=June 12, 2009 |title=Project 10 to the 100th |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=July 16, 2010 |deadurl=yes }}</ref> After two years of silence, during which many wondered what had happened to the program,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.wired.com/epicenter/2010/06/google-struggles-to-give-away-10-million/ |title=Google Struggles to Give Away $10&nbsp;million |last1=Van Burskirk |first1=Elliot |date=June 28, 2010 |work=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |accessdate=September 26, 2010}}</ref> Google revealed the winners of the project, giving a total of ten million dollars to various ideas ranging from non-profit organizations that promote education to a website that intends to make all legal documents public and online.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://googleblog.blogspot.com/2010/09/10-million-for-project-10100-winners.html |title=$10&nbsp;million for Project 10^100 winners |date=September 24, 2010 |last1=Twohill |first1=Lorraine |publisher=Google, Inc. |accessdate=September 26, 2010}}</ref>

In March 2007, in partnership with the [[Mathematical Sciences Research Institute]] (MSRI), Google hosted the first [[Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival]] at its headquarters in Mountain View.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qDL7yoz1TGQ The 2007 [[Julia Robinson Mathematics Festival]] at Google was the founding of this event for middle school and high school students.] video</ref> In 2011, Google donated 1&nbsp;million euros to [[International Mathematical Olympiad]] to support the next five annual International Mathematical Olympiads (2011–2015).<ref>{{cite web |first=Jill |last=Duffy |title=Mathletes Receive €1M Donation from Google |url=https://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2376099,00.asp |website=[[PC Magazine]] |publisher=[[Ziff Davis]] |date=January 21, 2011 |accessdate=March 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imo2011.nl/node/39 |title=Google donating 1&nbsp;million euros to IMO |date=January 20, 2011 |accessdate=February 4, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724154518/https://www.imo2011.nl/node/39 |archivedate=July 24, 2011 }}</ref> In July 2012, Google launched a "[[Legalize Love]]" campaign in support of [[gay rights]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2012/07/08/google-launches-legalise-love-gay-rights-campaign/ |title=Google launches 'Legalise Love' gay rights campaign |website=PinkNews.co.uk |accessdate=September 9, 2014}}</ref>

=== Tax avoidance ===
{{Further|Corporation tax in the Republic of Ireland#Multinational tax schemes}}

Google uses various [[Tax avoidance|tax avoidance strategies]]. Out of the [[List of the largest information technology companies|five largest American technology companies]], it pays the lowest taxes to the countries of origin of its revenues. Google between 2007 and 2010 saved $3.1 billion in taxes by shuttling non-U.S. profits through [[Ireland]] and the [[Netherlands]] and then to [[Bermuda]]. Such techniques lower its non-U.S. tax rate to 2.3 per cent, while normally the corporate tax rate in for instance the UK is 28 per cent.<ref>{{cite news |last=Metz |first=Cade |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2010/10/22/google_double_irish_tax_loophole/ |title=Google slips $3.1bn through 'Double Irish' tax loophole. |publisher=The Register |date=October 22, 2010}}</ref> This has reportedly sparked a French investigation into Google's [[transfer pricing]] practices.<ref>{{cite web |last=Leach |first=Anna |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/10/31/google_france_tax_office_billion_euros/ |title=French gov 'plans to hand Google €1bn tax bill'&nbsp;– report |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |date=October 31, 2012 |accessdate=January 2, 2013}}</ref>

Following criticism of the amount of corporate taxes that Google paid in the United Kingdom, Chairman Eric Schmidt said, "It's called capitalism. We are proudly capitalistic." During the same December 2012 interview, Schmidt confirmed that the company had no intention of paying more to the UK exchequer.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/home-news/google-boss-im-very-proud-of-our-tax-avoidance-scheme-8411974.html |title=Google boss: I'm very proud of our tax avoidance scheme |last1=Kumar |first1=Nikhil |last2=Wright |first2=Oliver |date=December 13, 2012 |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=December 17, 2012 |location=London}}</ref>

Google Vice-President [[Matt Brittin]] testified to the [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] of the UK House of Commons that his UK sales team made no sales and hence owed no sales taxes to the UK.<ref>{{cite web |author=Brid-Aine Parnell, May 17, 2013 |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/05/17/quotw_ending_may_17/ |title='I think you DO do evil, using smoke and mirrors to avoid tax' |publisher=Theregister.co.uk |date=May 17, 2013 |accessdate=March 13, 2014}}</ref> In January 2016, Google reached a settlement with the UK to pay £130m in back taxes plus higher taxes in future.<ref>{{cite web |author=John Gapper, January 23, 2016 |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/d50ad5f4-c125-11e5-9fdb-87b8d15baec2.html |title=Google strikes £130m back tax deal |publisher=FT.com |accessdate=January 24, 2016}}</ref>

=== Environment ===
{{As of|2007|since=y|post=,}} Google has aimed for carbon neutrality in regard to its operations.<ref>{{cite web |first=Jack |last=McGrath |title=Google's Green Initiative: Environmentally Conscious Technology |url=http://www.technobuffalo.com/2011/05/18/googles-green-initiative-environmentally-conscious-technology/ |publisher=''TechnoBuffalo'' |date=May 18, 2011 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}}</ref>

Google disclosed in September 2011 that it "continuously uses enough electricity to power 200,000 homes", almost 260 million watts or about a quarter of the output of a nuclear power plant. Total carbon emissions for 2010 were just under 1.5 million metric tons, mostly due to fossil fuels that provide electricity for the data centers. Google said that 25 percent of its energy was supplied by renewable fuels in 2010. An average search uses only 0.3 watt-hours of electricity, so all global searches are only 12.5 million watts or 5% of the total electricity consumption by Google.<ref>{{cite web |first=James |last=Glanz |title=Google Details, and Defends, Its Use of Electricity |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/09/technology/google-details-and-defends-its-use-of-electricity.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 8, 2011 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

In 2007, Google launched a project centered on developing renewable energy, titled the "Renewable Energy Cheaper than Coal (RE<C)" project.<ref>{{cite web |title=Google's Goal: Renewable Energy Cheaper than Coal |url=http://googlepress.blogspot.no/2007/11/googles-goal-renewable-energy-cheaper_27.html |date=November 27, 2007 |accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref> However, the project was canceled in 2014, after engineers Ross Koningstein and David Fork understood, after years of study, that "best-case scenario, which was based on our most optimistic forecasts for renewable energy, would still result in severe climate change", writing that they "came to the conclusion that even if Google and others had led the way toward a wholesale adoption of renewable energy, that switch would not have resulted in significant reductions in carbon dioxide emissions".<ref>{{cite web |first1=Ross |last1=Koningstein |first2=David |last2=Fork |title=What It Would Really Take to Reverse Climate Change |url=http://spectrum.ieee.org/energy/renewables/what-it-would-really-take-to-reverse-climate-change |publisher=''IEEE Spectrum'' |date=November 18, 2014 |accessdate=November 11, 2016}}</ref>

In June 2013, ''The Washington Post'' reported that Google had donated $50,000 to the [[Competitive Enterprise Institute]], a [[Libertarianism|libertarian]] [[think tank]] that calls human carbon emissions a positive factor in the environment and argues that global warming is not a concern.<ref>{{cite news |title=Anatomy of a Washington dinner: Who funds the Competitive Enterprise Institute? |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2013/06/20/anatomy-of-a-washington-dinner-who-funds-the-competitive-enterprise-institute/ |accessdate=July 12, 2013 |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=June 20, 2013 |author=Juliet Eilperin}}</ref>

In July 2013, it was reported that Google had hosted a fundraising event for Oklahoma Senator [[Jim Inhofe]], who has called climate change a "hoax".<ref>{{cite news |title=Google hosts fundraiser for climate change denying US senator |url=https://www.theguardian.com/environment/2013/jul/09/google-climate-denier-jim-inhofe |accessdate=July 12, 2013 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=July 9, 2013 |author=Suzanne Goldenberg |location=London}}</ref> In 2014 Google cut ties with the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]] (ALEC) after pressure from the Sierra Club, major unions and Google's own scientists because of ALEC's stance on climate change and opposition to renewable energy.<ref name=LA>{{cite news |title=Google pulls out of conservative group amid environmentalist pressure |author=EVAN HALPER |date=September 23, 2014 |work=Los Angeles Times |url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-google-gop-20140924-story.html |accessdate=October 3, 2014}}</ref>

In November 2017, Google bought 536 megawatts of wind power. The purchase made the firm reach 100% renewable energy. The wind energy comes from two power plants in South Dakota, one in Iowa and one in Oklahoma.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://fortune.com/2017/12/01/google-clean-energy/ |title= Google Just Bought Enough Wind Power to Run 100% On Renewable Energy |date= November 30, 2017 |author= Grace Donnelly |work= Fortune}}</ref>

=== Lobbying ===
In 2013, Google ranked 5th in [[Lobbying in the United States|lobbying]] spending, up from 213th in 2003. In 2012, the company ranked 2nd in campaign donations of technology and Internet sections.<ref name=lobby1>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/how-google-is-transforming-power-and-politicsgoogle-once-disdainful-of-lobbying-now-a-master-of-washington-influence/2014/04/12/51648b92-b4d3-11e3-8cb6-284052554d74_story.html |title=Google, once disdainful of lobbying, now a master of Washington influence |work=[[The Washington Post]] |first1=Tom |last1=Hamburger |first2=Matea |last2=Gold |date=April 13, 2014}}</ref>

=== Litigation ===
{{main|Google litigation}}

Google has been involved in a number of lawsuits including the [[High-Tech Employee Antitrust Litigation]] which resulted in Google being one of four companies to pay a $415 million settlement to employees.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rosenblatt |first=Joel |title=Apple-Google $415 Million No-Poaching Accord Wins Approval |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-03-02/tech-no-poaching-settlement-gets-judge-s-preliminary-approval |accessdate=January 24, 2016 |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=March 2, 2015}}</ref>

On June 27, 2017, the company received a record fine of {{€|2.42 billion|link=yes}} from the [[European Union]] for "promoting its own shopping comparison service at the top of search results."<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-40406542 |title=Google hit with record EU fine over Shopping service |first=Leo |last=Kelion |date=June 27, 2017 |publisher=bbc.co.uk |accessdate=June 29, 2017}}</ref> Commenting on the penalty, ''[[New Scientist]]'' magazine said: "The hefty sum – the largest ever doled out by the EU's competition regulators – will sting in the short term, but Google can handle it. Alphabet, Google’s parent company, made a profit of $2.5 billion (€2.2 billion) in the first six weeks of 2017 alone. The real impact of the ruling is that Google must stop using its dominance as a search engine to give itself the edge in another market: online price comparisons." The company disputed the ruling.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2139097-googles-e2-4bn-fine-is-small-change-the-eu-has-bigger-plans/ |title=Google's €2.4bn fine is small change – the EU has bigger plans |publisher=newscientist.com |accessdate=June 29, 2017}}</ref>

== Criticism and controversy ==
{{main|Criticism of Google|Censorship by Google}}

Google's market dominance has led to prominent media coverage, including [[Criticism of Google|criticism of the company]] over issues such as [[Google tax avoidance|aggressive tax avoidance]],<ref>{{cite web |first=Jesse |last=Drucker |title=Google 2.4% Rate Shows How $60 Billion Is Lost to Tax Loopholes |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2010-10-21/google-2-4-rate-shows-how-60-billion-u-s-revenue-lost-to-tax-loopholes |website=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |publisher=[[Bloomberg L.P.]] |date=October 21, 2010 |accessdate=January 22, 2017}} {{subscription required}}</ref> [[Criticism of Google#Page rank|search neutrality]], [[Criticism of Google#Copyright issues|copyright]], [[censorship by Google|censorship]] of search results and content,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/20/magazine/the-case-against-google.html |title=The Case Against Google |website=nytimes.com |date=February 20, 2018 |accessdate=March 21, 2018}}</ref> and [[Google privacy|privacy]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/technology/6740075.stm |work=BBC News |title=Google ranked 'worst' on privacy |date=June 11, 2007 |accessdate=April 30, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Jeffrey |last=Rosen |title=Google's Gatekeepers |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/11/30/magazine/30google-t.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=November 28, 2008 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref> Other criticisms include alleged misuse and manipulation of search results, its use of others' [[intellectual property]], concerns that its [[Data collection|compilation of data]] may violate people's [[Internet privacy|privacy]], and the [[energy consumption]] of its servers, as well as concerns over traditional business issues such as [[monopoly]], [[restraint of trade]], [[anti-competitive practices]], and [[patent infringement]].

Google adhered to the [[Internet censorship in the People's Republic of China|Internet censorship policies of China]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/technology/4645596.stm|title=Google censors itself for China|last=|first=|date=January 25, 2006|work=|publisher=BBC News|via=}}</ref> enforced by means of filters colloquially known as "The [[Great Firewall of China]]". ''The Intercept'' reported in August 2018 that Google is developing for the people's Republic of China a censored version of its search engine (known as [[Dragonfly (search engine)|Dragonfly]]) "that will blacklist websites and search terms about human rights, democracy, religion, and peaceful protest".<ref>{{cite news |title=Google Plans to Launch Censored Search Engine in China, Leaked Documents Reveal · Ryan Gallagher |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/08/01/google-china-search-engine-censorship/ |work=The Intercept |date=August 1, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Disis |first=Jill|title=Google grilled over 'Project Dragonfly' at Senate hearing on data privacy |date=26 September 2018 |newspaper=CNN |url=https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/26/technology/google-dragonfly-senate-hearing/index.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180926222719/https://money.cnn.com/2018/09/26/technology/google-dragonfly-senate-hearing/index.html |archive-date=26 September 2018 |dead-url=no |df=dmy}}</ref>

Google's [[mission statement]], from the outset, was "to organize the world's information and make it universally accessible and useful",<ref>{{cite web |first=Samuel |last=Gibbs |title=Google has 'outgrown' its 14-year old mission statement, says Larry Page |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/nov/03/larry-page-google-dont-be-evil-sergey-brin |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=November 3, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> and its unofficial slogan is "[[Don't be evil]]".<ref>{{cite web |title=Google Code of Conduct |url=https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html |website=Alphabet Investor Relations |publisher=[[Alphabet Inc.]] |date=April 11, 2012 |accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> In October 2015, a related motto was adopted in the Alphabet corporate code of conduct by the phrase: "Do the right thing".<ref>{{cite web |first=Richard |last=Lawler |title=Alphabet replaces Google's 'Don't be evil' with 'Do the right thing' |url=https://www.engadget.com/2015/10/02/alphabet-do-the-right-thing/ |website=[[Engadget]] |publisher=[[AOL]] |date=October 2, 2015 |accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> The original motto was retained in the code of conduct of Google, now a subsidiary of Alphabet.<ref name=":0">{{cite web|url=https://abc.xyz/investor/other/google-code-of-conduct.html|title=Google Code of Conduct|publisher=Alphabet|accessdate=August 31, 2017}}</ref>

Google's commitment to such robust idealism has been increasingly called into doubt due to a number of the firm's actions and behaviors which appear to contradict this.<ref>{{cite web |first=Holly |last=Baxter |title=Who's more evil – Facebook or Google? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/oct/25/evil-facebook-google-beheading-email-abuse |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=October 25, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Roxane |last=Gay |title=The Blog That Disappeared |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/30/opinion/sunday/the-blog-that-disappeared.html |website=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 29, 2016 |accessdate=March 9, 2017}}</ref>

Following media reports about [[PRISM (surveillance program)|PRISM]], NSA's massive electronic [[Mass surveillance|surveillance program]], in June 2013, several technology companies were identified as participants, including Google.<ref>{{cite web |title=Edward Snowden: Leaks that exposed US spy programme |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-23123964 |website=[[BBC News]] |date=January 17, 2014 |accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref> According to leaks of said program, Google joined the PRISM program in 2009.<ref>{{cite web |first1=Glenn |last1=Greenwald |first2=Ewen |last2=MacAskill |title=NSA Prism program taps in to user data of Apple, Google and others |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jun/06/us-tech-giants-nsa-data |website=[[The Guardian]] |publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]] |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=March 25, 2017}}</ref>

On August 8, 2017, Google fired employee James Damore after he distributed [[Google memo|a memo]] throughout the company which argued that "Google's ideological echo chamber" and bias clouded their thinking about diversity and inclusion, and that it is also biological factors, not discrimination alone, that cause the average woman to be less interested than men in technical positions.<ref name=NYTFired>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/07/business/google-women-engineer-fired-memo.html Google Fires Engineer Who Wrote Memo Questioning Women in Tech]. ''[[The New York Times]], August 7, 2017</ref> Google CEO Sundar Pichai accused Damore in violating company policy by "advancing harmful gender stereotypes in our workplace", and he was fired on the same day.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/08/technology/google-engineer-fired-gender-memo.html Contentious Memo Strikes Nerve Inside Google and Out]. ''[[The New York Times]]'', August 8, 2017</ref><ref>diversitymemo.com</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/the-most-common-error-in-coverage-of-the-google-memo/536181/ |title=The Most Common Error in Media Coverage of the Google Memo |first=Conor |last=Friedersdorf |publisher=}}</ref> ''New York Times'' columnist [[David Brooks (political commentator)|David Brooks]] argued Pichai had mishandled the case, and called for his resignation.<ref name="BrooksNYT">{{cite web |last=Brooks |first=David |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/opinion/sundar-pichai-google-memo-diversity.html |title=Sundar Pichai Should Resign as Google's C.E.O |website=The New York Times |date=August 11, 2017 |accessdate=August 11, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170811124216/https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/11/opinion/sundar-pichai-google-memo-diversity.html |archivedate=August 11, 2017  |url-access=limited}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.businessinsider.com/david-brooks-sundar-pichai-resignation-james-damore-2017-8 |title=New York Times columnist David Brooks wants Google's CEO to resign |website=Business Insider |language=en |access-date=August 12, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20170812131604/http://www.businessinsider.com/david-brooks-sundar-pichai-resignation-james-damore-2017-8 |archivedate=August 12, 2017 }}</ref>

Reportedly, Google's influenced [[New America (organization)|New America]] think tank to expel their Open Markets research group, after the group has criticized Google monopolistic power and supported the [[European Union vs. Google|EU $2.7B fine of Google]].<ref>{{Citation |last=Vogel |first=Kenneth P. | author-link = Kenneth Vogel |title=Google Critic Ousted From Think Tank Funded by the Tech Giant |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |pages=A1  |date=August 31, 2017 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/30/us/politics/eric-schmidt-google-new-america.html | access-date = September 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://citizensagainstmonopoly.org/ |title=Tell Google: Stop Killing Monopoly Research |website=citizensagainstmonopoly.org}}</ref>

Google has worked with the [[United States Department of Defense]] on drone software through the 2017 "Project Maven" that could be used to improve the accuracy of [[drone strike]]s.<ref>"[https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/04/google-should-not-be-in-the-business-of-war-googlers-decry-pentagon-project/ Google employees revolt, say company should shut down military drone project]". ''[[Ars Technica]]''. April 4, 2018.</ref> Thousands of Google employees, including senior engineers, have signed a letter urging Google CEO [[Sundar Pichai]] to end a controversial contract with the Pentagon.<ref>"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/business/news/google-protest-pentagon-drones-programme-company-sundar-pichai-department-of-defense-a8290111.html Google staff protest company's involvement with Pentagon drones programme]". ''The Independent''. April 4, 2018.</ref> In response to the backlash, Google ultimately decided to not review their DoD contract, set to expire in 2019.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Wakabayashi, Daisuke |author2=Shane, Scott |title=Google Will Not Renew Pentagon Contract That Upset Employees |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/06/01/technology/google-pentagon-project-maven.html |website=nytimes.com |publisher=The New York Times Company |accessdate=16 October 2018 |date=1 June 2018}}</ref>

=== Legal controversies ===
In 2017, David Elliot and Chris Gillespie argued before the [[Ninth Circuit of the United States Court of Appeals]] that "google" had suffered [[genericide]]. The controversy began in 2012 when Gillespie acquired 763 domain names containing the word "google." Google promptly filed a complaint with the [[National Arbitration Forum]] (NAF). Elliot then filed a petition for canceling the Google trademark. Ultimately, the court ruled in favor of Google because Elliot failed to show a preponderance of evidence showing the genericide of "google."<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca9/15-15809/15-15809-2017-05-16.html|title=Elliott v. Google, Inc., No. 15-15809 (9th Cir. 2017)|work=Justia Law|access-date=November 28, 2017|language=en}}</ref>

