'''Marthe Gosteli''' (22 December 1917 – 7 April 2017) was a Swiss suffrage activist and archivist. For thirty years, she led the fight for [[Women's suffrage|women's right to vote]] in Switzerland and then focused her attention on preserving the history of Swiss women. Creating an archive of women's biographies and history, Gosteli's work was recognized by many honors and awards, including the 2011 Swiss Human Rights Award.

==Biography==
Marthe Gosteli was born on 22 December 1917 in [[Worblaufen]], (now known as Ittigen) [[Switzerland]] to Johanna Ida (née Salzmann) and Ernst Gosteli. She completed commercial training and took language courses in the [[Romandy|French-speaking part of Switzerland]] and in [[London]].{{sfn|Ludi|2005}} Gosteli's father died, leaving his wife in charge of the estate. With the help of her daughters, the women managed to hold on to and maintain the family farm, but Gosteli recognized how inequality affected them{{sfn|Gatten|2015}} and joined the feminist movement in 1940.{{sfn|Hettinger|2012}}

During [[World War II]] Gosteli worked for the [[Wartime Broadcasting Service]] of the army staff.{{sfn|Berthoud|2011}} After the war between 1949 and 1953 and again from 1955 to 1962, she headed the film department of the Information Service at the US Embassy in Bern.{{sfn|Ludi|2005}} In the mid-1960s she turned her full focus toward the woman's movement.{{sfn|Berthoud|2011}} Gosteli became president of the Women's Suffrage Association ({{lang-de|Bernischer Frauenstimmrechtsverein}}) of [[Bern]] in 1964. She wrote pamphlets and went door-to-door trying to introduce equality gently. Rather than a demand for rights, Gosteli's approach focused on increasing women's participation in their communities,{{sfn|Hettinger|2012}} as she feared a demand would be resisted by the all-male referendum process.{{sfn|Gatten|2015}} After four years, she became vice president of the [[Bund Schweizerischer Frauenvereine|Federation of Swiss Women's Associations]] ({{lang-de|Bund Schweizerischer Frauenorganisationen}}) (BSF), and known now as Alliance F.{{sfn|Berthoud|2011}}
Gosteli became chair of the working group of the BSF for the Political Rights of Women in 1970{{sfn|Berthoud|2011}} and the women targeted the [[Swiss referendums, 1971|1971 referendum]], participating in various commissions{{sfn|Ludi|2005}} and debates. Finally, on 7 February 1971,{{sfn|Hettinger|2012}} two-thirds of the voting men in Switzerland granted women the right to vote at the national level.{{sfn|Gatten|2015}}

Quickly the fight then turned toward other inequalities: the right to manage their own bank accounts, equal pay, maternal leave and other women's issues.{{sfn|Gatten|2015}} Gosteli focused her attention on preserving the history of the movement, but her first attempt at establishing an archive of women's history failed. In 1982, she succeeded in establishing the Gosteli Foundation, to preserve and protect the history of Switzerland's women. Starting with a government collection of 19th century works including books, brochures and magazines, Gosteli added to the collection with private donations from organizations and individuals. Cataloging and adding the data to the information network of the German-Swiss archive ''Informationsverbund Deutschschweiz'' (IDS),{{sfn|Hettinger|2012}} the collection grew into an extensive library, which includes historic and biographical material about pioneers and organizations.{{sfn|Berthoud|2011}} In January 2014, at the age of 96, Gosteli retired from the archive.{{sfn|Fehlmann|2013}} 

She died on 7 April 2017 at the age of 99.{{sfn|Christ|2017}}

==Awards and honors==
Gosteli received many awards and honors. In 1989 she received the Trudy-Schlatter Prize and in 1992 was honored with the Medal of the Community of Bern. Gosteli was granted an Honorary doctorate from the [[University of Bern]].{{sfn|Ludi|2005}} In 2008, Gosteli received the Silver Medal of Merit from the Economic and Charitable Society of Bern{{sfn|OGG Bulletin|2008}} and in 2011 she was granted the Swiss Human Rights Award.{{sfn|''Berner Zeitung''|2011}}

