{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}} {{Infobox writer | name = Mustafa Zaidi | image = | imagesize = | caption = | pseudonym = Tegh Allahbadi | birth_name = Syed Mustafa Hasnain Zaidi | birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1930|10|10}} | birth_place = [[Allahabad|Allahabad, India]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1970|10|12|1930|10|10}} | death_place = | occupation = Poet | nationality = [[Pakistanis|Pakistani]] | ethnicity = | citizenship = | education = | alma_mater = | period = | genre = [[Nazm]]s and [[Ghazal]]s | subject = | movement = | notableworks = | spouse = Vera Zaidi | partner = | children = | relatives = Syed Lakhte Hussain Zaidi (father) | awards = [[Tamgha-e-Quaid-e-Azam]] | signature = }}
'''Mustafa Zaidi''' ({{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq| مصطفیٰ زیدی}}}}) (1930–1970), Born Syed Mustafa Hasnain Zaidi, was a [[Pakistani]] [[Urdu]] poet.
==Life== Mustafa Zaidi was born as Syed Mustafa Hasnain Zaidi on 10 Oct 1930 in [[Allahabad]]. He completed his Master of Arts in English literature in 1952 from the Government College, [[Lahore]]. Initially, he taught at [[Karachi]]'s Islamia College and then at [[Peshawar University]]. In 1954, he passed the competitive examination and was sent to [[England]] for training before being given the posts of deputy commissioner and deputy secretary.<ref name="Dawn 2008">{{cite web|title=Mustafa Zaidi: murder or suicide?|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/971951/mustafa-zaidi-murder-or-suicide|website=[[DAWN (newspaper)|DAWN]]|accessdate=13 October 2015|date=14 October 2008}}</ref>
He married Vera Zaidi, a [[Germans|German]] woman. They had two children, a boy and a girl.<ref name="Ali 2014">{{cite web | last=Ali | first=Kamran Asdar | title=COLUMN: A moment in Karachi’s history: a poet’s death remembered | website=DAWN.COM | date=2014-12-01 |url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1148084 | access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref>
He died on 12 October 1970 in [[Karachi]] under mysterious circumstances.<ref name="Ahmar1999">{{cite book|author=Yunus Ahmar|title=Modern Urdu Poets|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XPtCu5zdg-0C&pg=PA101|accessdate=15 February 2018|year=1999|publisher=Adam Publishers and Distributors|location=New Delhi|isbn=978-81-7435-162-3|page=101}}</ref><ref name="Parekh 2015">{{cite web | last=Parekh | first=Rauf | title=Creativity and mental disorder: Urdu poets and writers who committed suicide | website=DAWN.COM | date=2015-04-27 | url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1178438 | access-date=2018-02-14}}</ref>
==Works== He also wrote under his pen-name '''Tegh Allahabadi'''. His initial poetry was romantic in nature. At the age of 17, published his first collection of poetry ''Zanjeeren'' in 1949, followed by, ''Zangeerein'' (1949), ''Roshni'' (1950), ''Shehr-e-Azar'' (City of Idol Worshippers; 1958), ''Mauj Meri Sadaf Sadaf'' (1960), ''Gareban'' (1964), ''Qaba-e-Saaz'' (1967) and ''Koh-e-Nida'' (1971) (published posthumously). His complete work was published as ''Kulliyaat-i-Mustafa Zaidi'' posthumously.<ref name="Dawn 2008"/>
